{"title_page": "Saint Bede Catholic Church (Williamsburg, Virginia)", "text_new": "{{Infobox church\n|name                   = Saint Bede Catholic Church\n|image                  = Saint Bede Catholic Church, Williamsburg in March 2020.jpg \n|imagesize              = \n|imagelink              = \n|imagealt               = \n|landscape              = \n|caption                = New church of Saint Bede parish\n|location               = [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]], [[Virginia]]\n|country                = [[United States]]\n|denomination           = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]\n|membership             = \n|attendance             = \n|website                = {{URL|https://www.bedeva.org}}\n|founded date           = 1932\n|founder                = [[Andrew Brennan (bishop)|Bishop Andrew Brennan]]\n|dedication             = [[Bede|St. Bede]] <br> [[Our Lady of Walsingham]]\n|relics                 = \n|events                 = \n|past bishop            = \n|people                 = \n|status                 = Active\n|functional status      = \n|heritage designation   = \n|designated date        = \n|architect              = 2003 church: <br/> Tom Kerns, Sean Riley<ref name=organ>{{cite web |url=https://buzardorgans.com/buzard-opus-31/ |title=Buzard Opus 31 Williamsburg, Virginia |work=buzardorgans.com |publisher=John Paul Buzard Organ Builders |access-date=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211163629/https://buzardorgans.com/buzard-opus-31/ |archive-date=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n|architectural type     = \n|capacity               = \n|length                 = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|width                  = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|width nave             = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|height                 = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|bells                  = \n|bells hung             = \n|bell weight            = \n|parish                 = \n|archdiocese            = \n|diocese                = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Richmond|Diocese of Richmond]]\n|archbishop             = \n|bishop                 = [[Barry C. Knestout|Bishop Barry Knestout]]\n|priestincharge         = \n|priest                 = \n|asstpriest             = \n|minister               = \n|assistant              = \n|deacon                 = \n|director               = \n|organist               = \n|youthmin               = \n|musicgroup             = \n|parishadmin            = \n|serversguild           = \n|coordinates            = {{Coord|37.262107|N|76.755738|W|}}\n|embedded = \n}}\n'''Saint Bede Catholic Church''' in [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]], [[Virginia]] is a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] [[parish church|parish]] in the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Richmond|Diocese of Richmond]]. The '''National Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham''', located adjacent to the campus of the [[College of William and Mary]], is a part of the parish.<ref name=OurParishHistory>{{cite web|url=https://www.bedeva.org/parish-life/about|title=Our Parish History|publisher=Saint Bede Catholic Church|work=bedeva.org|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref>  It was the first Catholic church in Williamsburg.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Statue of Our Lady of Walsingham in Saint Bede Catholic Church, February 2020.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Statue of Our Lady of Walsingham on display in Saint Bede Catholic Church after being removed during renovations of the Shrine.]]\nThe first Catholics in the [[Virginia Peninsula]] were two [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] friars, accompanied by 37 Spanish and Portuguese troops and guided by a converted [[Algonquian peoples|Algonquian]], in August 1566. Ten Spanish [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] founded [[Ajac\u00e1n Mission|St. Mary's Mission]], known more commonly as the Ajac\u00e1n Mission, in 1570.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypress.com/history/dp-nws-spanish-mission-on-the-york-20130508-story.html|work=dailypress.org|publisher=Daily Press|last=Erickson|first=Mark|title=A lost Spanish mission on the York River|date=8 May 2013|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref> One posited location for where they disembarked is present-day [[College Creek]].<ref name=SpanishMartyrs>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalwalsinghamshrine.org/the-virginia-martyrs|title=The Virginia Martyrs|work=nationalwalsinghamshrine.org|publisher=National Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref> The entire encampment of Spanish missionaries and Native American converts was massacred by [[Powhatan|Powhatans]] in 1571 with the exception of a single convert boy, who was rescued by Spanish forces from [[Spanish Florida|Florida]] the next year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marinersmuseum.org/sites/micro/cbhf/colonial/col001.html|work=marinersmuseum.org|publisher=Mariners Museum|title=Colonial Period: Ajacan, The Spanish Jesuit Mission|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1923, [[Mexican Americans|Mexican immigrant]] and professor [[Carlos Casta\u00f1eda (historian)|Carlos Eduardo Casta\u00f1eda]] arrived at the College of William and Mary to teach [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. As the faculty leader of the Gibbons Club, formed on 11 December 1923, he and thirty students agitated for a priest from [[Newport News]] to come to Williamsburg in order to fulfill their [[Holy day of obligation|Sunday Mass obligations]].<ref name=page38>{{cite book|title=The Holy House: A History of the Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham Williamsburg, Virginia|last=Spike|first=Mich\u00e8le|date=2018|publisher=[[Legion of Mary]]|page=38}}</ref> In 1929, $25,000 was given by Margaret Burns to the Diocese of Richmond for \"mission churches in Virginia,\" with the money going towards two lots purchased with the support of College President [[J. A. C. Chandler]].<ref name=page38 />\n[[File:Banner at Saint Bede Catholic Church, Williamsburg, Virginia.png|thumb|180px|Banner for Saint Bede Church depicting Our Lady of Walsingham and coat of arms for the Diocese of Richmond.]]\n\nIn 1932, the Catholic College Chapel was constructed to meet the growing needs of the Catholic students and staff at the College. The chapel was dedicated to [[Benedictines|Benedictine]] [[Christian monasticism|monk]] [[Bede|St. Bede the Venerable]] in October 1932.<ref name=page38 /> In 1939, the chapel was dedicated as a parish.<ref name=OurParishHistory /> On 1 February 1942, Saint Bede's first pastor Fr. Thomas Walsh dedicated the parish to [[Our Lady of Walsingham]]. The church was blessed in 1942.<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalwalsinghamshrine.org/history|title=History|work=nationalwalsinghamshrine.org|publisher=National Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe parish purchased a building originally constructed as a [[Fraternities and sororities|fraternity]] home adjacent to the original location of Saint Bede, 601 College Terrace, for use as housing by the [[USO]], in which thousands of soldiers and families stayed. On 16 September 1947, the [[Sisters of Mercy]] opened [[Walsingham Academy]], a [[independent school|private]] Catholic school, in this building. After the school's move, the building served as a [[clergy house|rectory]] and is now a privately-owned home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walsingham.org/about/history|work=walsingham.org|publisher=Walsingham Academy|title=History|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the parish opened a church off of Ironbound Road in Williamsburg, about 1.5 miles from the original chapel. While the title of Saint Bede Catholic Church passed to this new structure, the National Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham remained a part of and is managed by the parish.<ref name=holyhouse>{{cite web|url=https://nationalwalsinghamshrine.org/restore-the-holy-house|access-date=10 February 2020|title=Restore the Holy House|publisher=National Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham|work=nationalwalsinghamshrine.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210193029/https://nationalwalsinghamshrine.org/restore-the-holy-house|archive-date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ordination of women in the Anglican Communion|ordination]] of [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal]] [[Diocese of Southern Virginia]] [[Bishop]] [[Susan Bunton Haynes|Susan Haynes]] was originally scheduled to take place on 1 February 2020 in Saint Bede.<ref name=Episcopal>{{cite web|url=http://images.acswebnetworks.com/1/2279/ConsecrationRelocationrelease2020.pdf|title=New location announced for the consecration of the 11th Bishop of the Episcopal Diocese of Southern Virginia|work=diosova.org|publisher=Episcopal Diocese of Southern Virginia|date=17 January 2020|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> Petitions seeking for Catholic Bishop [[Barry C. Knestout|Barry Knestout]] to rescind the invitation towards the Episcopalians resulted in international coverage of the controversy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://catholicherald.co.uk/news/2020/01/17/catholic-parish-will-no-longer-host-consecration-of-female-episcopalian-bishop/|title=Catholic parish will not host Episcopalian consecration|work=catholicherald.org|publisher=Catholic Herald|last=Rousselle|first=Christine|date=17 January 2020|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> On 17 January 2020, the Episcopal Diocese announced they were moving the ordination to a different church in Williamsburg, citing that the event was \"causing dismay and distress\" in the Saint Bede community and invoking the warning of [[Paul the Apostle|St. Paul]] against \"pursuing behavior that might cause problems for others within their community.\"<ref name=Episcopal /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.episcopalnewsservice.org/2020/01/22/southern-virginia-moves-female-bishop-consecration-in-response-to-backlash-from-roman-catholics/|title=Southern Virginia moves female bishop\u2019s consecration in response to backlash from Roman Catholics|work=episcopalnewsservice.org|publisher=Episcopal News Service|date=22 January 2020|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nLike other parishes in the Diocese of Richmond and [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion#Christianity|around the world]], the ongoing [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]] forced the cessation of public [[Mass (liturgy)|Masses]] and the cancellation of other parish activities on 15 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bedeva.org/446|title=COVID-19 Updates|work=bedeva.org|publisher=Saint Bede Catholic Church|date=15 March 2020|access-date=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317035716/https://www.bedeva.org/446|archive-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Parish==\nThe present location of the Saint Bede parish church is composed of a primary [[Church (building)|church]] and three [[wing (building)|wings]], two above ground and one beneath the courtyard. The wings were a 37,000 foot addition for the purpose of providing space for [[Koinonia|fellowship]] and community events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://guernseytingle.com/project/saint-bede-catholic-church/|publisher=GuernseyTingle|title=Saint Bede Catholic Church|access-date=7 February 2020}}</ref> The wings were completed in 2016 and also house the parish offices for finances and clergy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.catholicvirginian.org/?p=2655|title=Construction moves on at St. Bede\u2019s, Williamsburg|work=catholicvirginian.org|publisher=The Catholic Virginian|last=Neill|first=Steve|date=15 August 2016|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the church's [[pipe organ]] was completed.<ref name=organ/> It is named for the former pastor of Saint Bede Monsignor William H. Carr.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lis.virginia.gov/cgi-bin/legp604.exe?191+ful+SJ475+hil|title=SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION NO. 475 Offered February 18, 2019 Commending the Reverend Monsignor William H. Carr|author=Commonwealth of Virginia Senate|publisher=Legislative Information System|date=19 February 2019|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref> The main organ is {{convert|32|ft|m}} tall with 183 [[Key (instrument)|keys]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bedeva.org/103|work=bedeva.org|title=Pipe Organ|publisher=Saint Bede Catholic Church|access-date=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211165638/https://www.bedeva.org/103|archive-date=11 February 2020}}</ref> The organ features 54 ranks and 43 stops with pontifical trumpets in the separated processional organ. Due to [[Soundproofing|noise-dampening]] foam, there exist certain peculiarities in the organ's sound, such as the least favorable place to hear the organ being directly in front of it.<ref name=organ/>\n\nIn 2019, two [[mosaics]] were added to the church, flanking the organ. The mosaics, produced by [[Italy|Italian]] mosaic studio Ferrari & Bacci, depict the [[communion of saints|communion of]] [[saint|saints]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://m.facebook.com/story.php?story_fbid=2492151457718050&id=1492595331007006&__tn__=%2As%2As-R|title=Facebook update 5 March 2020|work=Ferra & Bacci Facebook Page|publisher=Facebook|date=5 March 2020|access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref> Eventually, there are plans to add further art on the 32 other panels that circle the church.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bedeva.org/370 |title=Sacred Art|work=bedeva.org|publisher=Saint Bede Catholic Church|access-date=7 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206214240/https://www.bedeva.org/370|archive-date=6 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bedeva.org/media/1/32/Sacred%20Art%20Announcement%20v(2)73118.pdf|title= Sacred Art Announcement|publisher=Saint Bede Catholic Church|date=18 August 2018|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Ministries and services===\nThere are over 60 ministries, social groups, and organizations that operate in or with the support of the Saint Bede parish, including:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bedeva.org/85|publisher=Saint Bede Catholic Church|work=bedeva.org|title=Parish Life Groups and Apostolates|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Knights of Columbus]]\n*[[Legion of Mary]]\n*[[Cub Scouting (Boy Scouts of America)|Cub Scouts]] and [[Boy Scouts of America|Boy Scouts]] Troops 1932\n*Hope [[Crisis pregnancy center|Pregnancy Resource Center]]\n*[[Ancient Order of Hibernians]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.catholicvirginian.org/?p=5331|title=The Ancient Order of Hibernians present check|work=catholicvirginian.org|publisher=The Catholic Virginian|date=29 June 2016|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n*Spanish- and English-language [[catechesis]]\n*House of Mercy, a service for the [[homelessness|homeless]] and economically marginalized that operates in a building adjacent to the Shrine.<ref name=HouseofMercy>{{cite web|url=https://www.williamsburghouseofmercy.org/pages/our-mission/our-history/|title=Our History|publisher=Williamsburg House of Mercy|work=williamsburghouseofmercy.org|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==National Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham==\nFr. Walsh was appointed the first pastor of Saint Bede and the College Chapel in 1939. With the 2 February 1942\u2013[[Feast of the Presentation of Christ in the Temple]]\u2013dedication of the Saint Bede parish to Our Lady of Walsingham, Fr. Walsh commissioned a statue depicting the [[Marian apparition]] done in the same style of that present at the [[Basilica of Our Lady of Walsingham|Slipper Chapel]], itself based on that from the [[Walsingham Priory]].<ref name=history /> The dedication of Saint Bede church to Our Lady of Walsingham is possibly attributable to Fr. Walsh's personal devotion to the apparition and visit to Europe in 1934 and possible pilgrimage to [[Walsingham]] that year.<ref name=Spike40>Spike, 40.</ref> In 2016, the [[United States Conference of Catholic Bishops]] recognized the Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham as the first [[national shrine]] in the Diocese of Richmond.<ref name=named>{{cite web|url=https://www.catholicvirginian.org/?p=1550|title=Walsingham in Williamsburg named national shrine|work=catholicvirginia.org|publisher=The Catholic Virginian|last=Allen|first=Greg|date=3 June 2016|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Williamsburg House of Mercy, a social outreach organization, is located on the campus of the Shrine. Formerly called the Saint Bede Outreach Center, it traces it legacy to the 1960s, when Sister Berenice Eltz left her teaching position at Walsingham Academy to serve in a social ministry role at Saint Bede parish.<ref name=HouseofMercy/> The Catholic Student Center is located on the bottom floor of the same building.<ref name=Center>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribecatholic.org/catholic-student-center|title=Catholic Student Center|publisher=William & Mary Catholic Campus Ministry|work=tribecatholic.org|access-date=10 February 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200219163259/https://www.tribecatholic.org/catholic-student-center|archive-date=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nSince the opening of the Ironbound church, the Shrine has been referred to as the \"Old Saint Bede\" and \"CCM Chapel\" in reference to the Catholic Campus Ministry that operates from it. Several renovations have been undertaken to expand the Shrine and meet [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990|ADA compliance standards]]. As of February 2020, the Shrine building is closed for further renovation; however, the adjacent House of Mercy building continues to host Mass for the downtown and college community.<ref name=holyhouse/>\n\nFor the 24 September Feast of Our Lady of Walsingham, congregants of both Saint Bede and Episcopal [[Bruton Parish Church|Bruton Parish]]\u2013along with their respective student ministries\u2013participate in an [[rosary]] [[Procession#Christian_processions|procession]] carrying the Marian statue from [[Colonial Williamsburg]] to the Shrine. At the Shrine, there are [[ecumenism|ecumenical]] [[vespers]].<ref name=named /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalwalsinghamshrine.org/feast-of-our-lady-of-walsingham|title=Upcoming Events: Feast of Our Lady of Walsingham|work=nationalwalsinghamshrine.org|publisher=National Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham|access-date=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211161331/https://www.nationalwalsinghamshrine.org/feast-of-our-lady-of-walsingham|archive-date=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Campus ministry===\n[[File:Covenant between William & Mary\u2019s Catholic Student Association and Canterbury, 1977.jpg|thumb|150px|Ecumenical covenant signed by Bishop [[Walter Francis Sullivan]] of the Diocese of Richmond and Bishop Coadjutor [[Charles Vach\u00e9]] of the [[Diocese of Southern Virginia]] and representatives from the Catholic Student Association and Canterbury at William & Mary]]\nIn 1865, the College reported a single Catholic student.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scdbwiki.swem.wm.edu/wiki/index.php/Religious_Beliefs_of_Students|title=Religious Beliefs of Students|work=Special Collections Research Center Wiki|publisher=William & Mary Libraries|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref> By 1939, 114 Catholics attended the College or lived in the nearby community.<ref name=Spike40/> As of 2019, an average of 225 students attend Sunday Mass at the Shrine, with an average of 25 students attending daily masses at the Shrine or in the [[Wren Building|Wren chapel]].<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210204628/https://www.tribecatholic.org/annualreport|url=https://www.tribecatholic.org/annualreport|title=Annual Report|publisher=William & Mary Catholic Campus Ministry|work=tribecatholic.org|access-date=10 February 2020|archive-date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Gibbons Club was founded in 1923, later renamed the [[Newman Center|Newman Club]] after the establishment of the parish.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scdbwiki.swem.wm.edu/wiki/index.php/Gibbons_Club|title=Gibbons Club|work=Special Collections Research Center Wiki|publisher=William & Mary Libraries|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref> The Newman Club was later renamed to the Catholic Student Association. Alongside their [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]] equivalent, Canterbury, the CSA signed a covenant\u2013committing both organizations to  ecumenical actions\u2013in the Wren Chapel on 24 January 1977. The CSA and Canterbury formerly cooperated in running a chapter of [[Covenant Players]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DaqLdYMaeB0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Camille+Thompson+college+of+William+and+mary&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi20ZmXz8fnAhXPmHIEHXLRABsQ6AEwAXoECAEQAg#v=onepage&q=Camille%20Thompson%20college%20of%20William%20and%20mary&f=false|page=155|last=Thompson|first=Camille|work=College Prowler|title=College of William and Mary: Off the Record|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref> The student ministry was again renamed to its present title, Catholic Campus Ministry, in line with the names of other campus ministries within the Diocese of Richmond.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribecatholic.org|title=Tribe Catholic|publisher=William & Mary Catholic Campus Ministry|work=tribecatholic.org|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://evangelizerichmond.org/campus/find-a-campus/|title=Find a Campus|publisher=Diocese of Richmond|author=Office of Evangelization|work=evangelizerichmond.org|access-date=11 February 2020}}</ref> The Catholic Student Center, located alongside the Shrine, is colloquially known as the \"Catacombs\" or \"Cats.\"<ref name=Center />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Richmond}}\n{{Catholic Church}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic national shrines in the United States]]\n[[Category:Churches in the Roman Catholic Diocese of Richmond]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Williamsburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Williamsburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Williamsburg, Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox church\n|name                   = Saint Bede Catholic Church\n|image                  = Saint Bede Catholic Church, Williamsburg in March 2020.jpg \n|imagesize              = \n|imagelink              = \n|imagealt               = \n|landscape              = \n|caption                = New church of Saint Bede parish\n|location               = [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]], [[Virginia]]\n|country                = [[United States]]\n|denomination           = [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]]\n|membership             = \n|attendance             = \n|website                = {{URL|https://www.bedeva.org}}\n|founded date           = 1932\n|founder                = [[Andrew Brennan (bishop)|Bishop Andrew Brennan]]\n|dedication             = [[Bede|St. Bede]] <br> [[Our Lady of Walsingham]]\n|relics                 = \n|events                 = \n|past bishop            = \n|people                 = \n|status                 = Active\n|functional status      = \n|heritage designation   = \n|designated date        = \n|architect              = 2003 church: <br/> Tom Kerns, Sean Riley<ref name=organ>{{cite web |url=https://buzardorgans.com/buzard-opus-31/ |title=Buzard Opus 31 Williamsburg, Virginia |work=buzardorgans.com |publisher=John Paul Buzard Organ Builders |access-date=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211163629/https://buzardorgans.com/buzard-opus-31/ |archive-date=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n|architectural type     = \n|capacity               = \n|length                 = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|width                  = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|width nave             = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|height                 = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|bells                  = \n|bells hung             = \n|bell weight            = \n|parish                 = \n|archdiocese            = \n|diocese                = [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Richmond|Diocese of Richmond]]\n|archbishop             = \n|bishop                 = [[Barry C. Knestout|Bishop Barry Knestout]]\n|priestincharge         = \n|priest                 = \n|asstpriest             = \n|minister               = \n|assistant              = \n|deacon                 = \n|director               = \n|organist               = \n|youthmin               = \n|musicgroup             = \n|parishadmin            = \n|serversguild           = \n|coordinates            = {{Coord|37.262107|N|76.755738|W|}}\n|embedded = \n}}\n'''Saint Bede Catholic Church''' in [[Williamsburg, Virginia|Williamsburg]], [[Virginia]] is a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] [[parish church|parish]] in the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Richmond|Diocese of Richmond]]. The '''National Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham''', located adjacent to the campus of the [[College of William and Mary]], is a part of the parish.<ref name=OurParishHistory>{{cite web|url=https://www.bedeva.org/parish-life/about|title=Our Parish History|publisher=Saint Bede Catholic Church|work=bedeva.org|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref>  It was the first Catholic church in Williamsburg.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Statue of Our Lady of Walsingham in Saint Bede Catholic Church, February 2020.jpg|thumb|150px|left|Statue of Our Lady of Walsingham on display in Saint Bede Catholic Church after being removed during renovations of the Shrine.]]\nThe first Catholics in the [[Virginia Peninsula]] were two [[Dominican Order|Dominican]] friars, accompanied by 37 Spanish and Portuguese troops and guided by a converted [[Algonquian]], in August 1566. Ten Spanish [[Society of Jesus|Jesuits]] founded [[Ajac\u00e1n Mission|St. Mary's Mission]], known more commonly as the Ajac\u00e1n Mission, in 1570.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dailypress.com/history/dp-nws-spanish-mission-on-the-york-20130508-story.html|work=dailypress.org|publisher=Daily Press|last=Erickson|first=Mark|title=A lost Spanish mission on the York River|date=8 May 2013|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref> One posited location for where they disembarked is present-day [[College Creek]].<ref name=SpanishMartyrs>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalwalsinghamshrine.org/the-virginia-martyrs|title=The Virginia Martyrs|work=nationalwalsinghamshrine.org|publisher=National Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref> The entire encampment of Spanish missionaries and Native American converts was massacred by [[Powhatan|Powhatans]] in 1571 with the exception of a single convert boy, who was rescued by Spanish forces from [[Spanish Florida|Florida]] the next year.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.marinersmuseum.org/sites/micro/cbhf/colonial/col001.html|work=marinersmuseum.org|publisher=Mariners Museum|title=Colonial Period: Ajacan, The Spanish Jesuit Mission|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn September 1923, [[Mexican Americans|Mexican immigrant]] and professor [[Carlos Casta\u00f1eda (historian)|Carlos Eduardo Casta\u00f1eda]] arrived at the College of William and Mary to teach [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. As the faculty leader of the Gibbons Club, formed on 11 December 1923, he and thirty students agitated for a priest from [[Newport News]] to come to Williamsburg in order to fulfill their [[Holy day of obligation|Sunday Mass obligations]].<ref name=page38>{{cite book|title=The Holy House: A History of the Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham Williamsburg, Virginia|last=Spike|first=Mich\u00e8le|date=2018|publisher=[[Legion of Mary]]|page=38}}</ref> In 1929, $25,000 was given by Margaret Burns to the Diocese of Richmond for \"mission churches in Virginia,\" with the money going towards two lots purchased with the support of College President [[J. A. C. Chandler]].<ref name=page38 />\n[[File:Banner at Saint Bede Catholic Church, Williamsburg, Virginia.png|thumb|180px|Banner for Saint Bede Church depicting Our Lady of Walsingham and coat of arms for the Diocese of Richmond.]]\n\nIn 1932, the Catholic College Chapel was constructed to meet the growing needs of the Catholic students and staff at the College. The chapel was dedicated to [[Benedictines|Benedictine]] [[Christian monasticism|monk]] [[Bede|St. Bede the Venerable]] in October 1932.<ref name=page38 /> In 1939, the chapel was dedicated as a parish.<ref name=OurParishHistory /> On 1 February 1942, Saint Bede's first pastor Fr. Thomas Walsh dedicated the parish to [[Our Lady of Walsingham]]. The church was blessed in 1942.<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalwalsinghamshrine.org/history|title=History|work=nationalwalsinghamshrine.org|publisher=National Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe parish purchased a building originally constructed as a [[Fraternities and sororities|fraternity]] home adjacent to the original location of Saint Bede, 601 College Terrace, for use as housing by the [[USO]], in which thousands of soldiers and families stayed. On 16 September 1947, the [[Sisters of Mercy]] opened [[Walsingham Academy]], a [[independent school|private]] Catholic school, in this building. After the school's move, the building served as a [[clergy house|rectory]] and is now a privately-owned home.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.walsingham.org/about/history|work=walsingham.org|publisher=Walsingham Academy|title=History|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, the parish opened a church off of Ironbound Road in Williamsburg, about 1.5 miles from the original chapel. While the title of Saint Bede Catholic Church passed to this new structure, the National Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham remained a part of and is managed by the parish.<ref name=holyhouse>{{cite web|url=https://nationalwalsinghamshrine.org/restore-the-holy-house|access-date=10 February 2020|title=Restore the Holy House|publisher=National Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham|work=nationalwalsinghamshrine.org|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210193029/https://nationalwalsinghamshrine.org/restore-the-holy-house|archive-date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Ordination of women in the Anglican Communion|ordination]] of [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopal]] [[Diocese of Southern Virginia]] [[Bishop]] [[Susan Bunton Haynes|Susan Haynes]] was originally scheduled to take place on 1 February 2020 in Saint Bede.<ref name=Episcopal>{{cite web|url=http://images.acswebnetworks.com/1/2279/ConsecrationRelocationrelease2020.pdf|title=New location announced for the consecration of the 11th Bishop of the Episcopal Diocese of Southern Virginia|work=diosova.org|publisher=Episcopal Diocese of Southern Virginia|date=17 January 2020|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> Petitions seeking for Catholic Bishop [[Barry C. Knestout|Barry Knestout]] to rescind the invitation towards the Episcopalians resulted in international coverage of the controversy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://catholicherald.co.uk/news/2020/01/17/catholic-parish-will-no-longer-host-consecration-of-female-episcopalian-bishop/|title=Catholic parish will not host Episcopalian consecration|work=catholicherald.org|publisher=Catholic Herald|last=Rousselle|first=Christine|date=17 January 2020|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref> On 17 January 2020, the Episcopal Diocese announced they were moving the ordination to a different church in Williamsburg, citing that the event was \"causing dismay and distress\" in the Saint Bede community and invoking the warning of [[Paul the Apostle|St. Paul]] against \"pursuing behavior that might cause problems for others within their community.\"<ref name=Episcopal /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.episcopalnewsservice.org/2020/01/22/southern-virginia-moves-female-bishop-consecration-in-response-to-backlash-from-roman-catholics/|title=Southern Virginia moves female bishop\u2019s consecration in response to backlash from Roman Catholics|work=episcopalnewsservice.org|publisher=Episcopal News Service|date=22 January 2020|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nLike other parishes in the Diocese of Richmond and [[Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on religion#Christianity|around the world]], the ongoing [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 pandemic]] forced the cessation of public [[Mass (liturgy)|Masses]] and the cancellation of other parish activities on 15 March 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bedeva.org/446|title=COVID-19 Updates|work=bedeva.org|publisher=Saint Bede Catholic Church|date=15 March 2020|access-date=16 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200317035716/https://www.bedeva.org/446|archive-date=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Parish==\nThe present location of the Saint Bede parish church is composed of a primary [[Church (building)|church]] and three [[wing (building)|wings]], two above ground and one beneath the courtyard. The wings were a 37,000 foot addition for the purpose of providing space for [[Koinonia|fellowship]] and community events.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://guernseytingle.com/project/saint-bede-catholic-church/|publisher=GuernseyTingle|title=Saint Bede Catholic Church|access-date=7 February 2020}}</ref> The wings were completed in 2016 and also house the parish offices for finances and clergy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.catholicvirginian.org/?p=2655|title=Construction moves on at St. Bede\u2019s, Williamsburg|work=catholicvirginian.org|publisher=The Catholic Virginian|last=Neill|first=Steve|date=15 August 2016|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, the church's [[pipe organ]] was completed.<ref name=organ/> It is named for the former pastor of Saint Bede Monsignor William H. Carr.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lis.virginia.gov/cgi-bin/legp604.exe?191+ful+SJ475+hil|title=SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION NO. 475 Offered February 18, 2019 Commending the Reverend Monsignor William H. Carr|author=Commonwealth of Virginia Senate|publisher=Legislative Information System|date=19 February 2019|access-date=1 March 2020}}</ref> The main organ is {{convert|32|ft|m}} tall with 183 [[Key (instrument)|keys]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bedeva.org/103|work=bedeva.org|title=Pipe Organ|publisher=Saint Bede Catholic Church|access-date=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211165638/https://www.bedeva.org/103|archive-date=11 February 2020}}</ref> The organ features 54 ranks and 43 stops with pontifical trumpets in the separated processional organ. Due to [[Soundproofing|noise-dampening]] foam, there exist certain peculiarities in the organ's sound, such as the least favorable place to hear the organ being directly in front of it.<ref name=organ/>\n\nIn 2019, two [[mosaics]] were added to the church, flanking the organ. The mosaics, produced by [[Italy|Italian]] mosaic studio Ferrari & Bacci, depict the [[communion of saints|communion of]] [[saint|saints]].<ref>{{cite web|url= https://m.facebook.com/story.php?story_fbid=2492151457718050&id=1492595331007006&__tn__=%2As%2As-R|title=Facebook update 5 March 2020|work=Ferra & Bacci Facebook Page|publisher=Facebook|date=5 March 2020|access-date=8 March 2020}}</ref> Eventually, there are plans to add further art on the 32 other panels that circle the church.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bedeva.org/370 |title=Sacred Art|work=bedeva.org|publisher=Saint Bede Catholic Church|access-date=7 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200206214240/https://www.bedeva.org/370|archive-date=6 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.bedeva.org/media/1/32/Sacred%20Art%20Announcement%20v(2)73118.pdf|title= Sacred Art Announcement|publisher=Saint Bede Catholic Church|date=18 August 2018|access-date=7 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Ministries and services===\nThere are over 60 ministries, social groups, and organizations that operate in or with the support of the Saint Bede parish, including:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bedeva.org/85|publisher=Saint Bede Catholic Church|work=bedeva.org|title=Parish Life Groups and Apostolates|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Knights of Columbus]]\n*[[Legion of Mary]]\n*[[Cub Scouting (Boy Scouts of America)|Cub Scouts]] and [[Boy Scouts of America|Boy Scouts]] Troops 1932\n*Hope [[Crisis pregnancy center|Pregnancy Resource Center]]\n*[[Ancient Order of Hibernians]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.catholicvirginian.org/?p=5331|title=The Ancient Order of Hibernians present check|work=catholicvirginian.org|publisher=The Catholic Virginian|date=29 June 2016|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n*Spanish- and English-language [[catechesis]]\n*House of Mercy, a service for the [[homelessness|homeless]] and economically marginalized that operates in a building adjacent to the Shrine.<ref name=HouseofMercy>{{cite web|url=https://www.williamsburghouseofmercy.org/pages/our-mission/our-history/|title=Our History|publisher=Williamsburg House of Mercy|work=williamsburghouseofmercy.org|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==National Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham==\nFr. Walsh was appointed the first pastor of Saint Bede and the College Chapel in 1939. With the 2 February 1942\u2013[[Feast of the Presentation of Christ in the Temple]]\u2013dedication of the Saint Bede parish to Our Lady of Walsingham, Fr. Walsh commissioned a statue depicting the [[Marian apparition]] done in the same style of that present at the [[Basilica of Our Lady of Walsingham|Slipper Chapel]], itself based on that from the [[Walsingham Priory]].<ref name=history /> The dedication of Saint Bede church to Our Lady of Walsingham is possibly attributable to Fr. Walsh's personal devotion to the apparition and visit to Europe in 1934 and possible pilgrimage to [[Walsingham]] that year.<ref name=Spike40>Spike, 40.</ref> In 2016, the [[United States Conference of Catholic Bishops]] recognized the Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham as the first [[national shrine]] in the Diocese of Richmond.<ref name=named>{{cite web|url=https://www.catholicvirginian.org/?p=1550|title=Walsingham in Williamsburg named national shrine|work=catholicvirginia.org|publisher=The Catholic Virginian|last=Allen|first=Greg|date=3 June 2016|access-date=12 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Williamsburg House of Mercy, a social outreach organization, is located on the campus of the Shrine. Formerly called the Saint Bede Outreach Center, it traces it legacy to the 1960s, when Sister Berenice Eltz left her teaching position at Walsingham Academy to serve in a social ministry role at Saint Bede parish.<ref name=HouseofMercy/> The Catholic Student Center is located on the bottom floor of the same building.<ref name=Center>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribecatholic.org/catholic-student-center|title=Catholic Student Center|publisher=William & Mary Catholic Campus Ministry|work=tribecatholic.org|access-date=10 February 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200219163259/https://www.tribecatholic.org/catholic-student-center|archive-date=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nSince the opening of the Ironbound church, the Shrine has been referred to as the \"Old Saint Bede\" and \"CCM Chapel\" in reference to the Catholic Campus Ministry that operates from it. Several renovations have been undertaken to expand the Shrine and meet [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990|ADA compliance standards]]. As of February 2020, the Shrine building is closed for further renovation; however, the adjacent House of Mercy building continues to host Mass for the downtown and college community.<ref name=holyhouse/>\n\nFor the 24 September Feast of Our Lady of Walsingham, congregants of both Saint Bede and Episcopal [[Bruton Parish Church|Bruton Parish]]\u2013along with their respective student ministries\u2013participate in an [[rosary]] [[Procession#Christian_processions|procession]] carrying the Marian statue from [[Colonial Williamsburg]] to the Shrine. At the Shrine, there are [[ecumenism|ecumenical]] [[vespers]].<ref name=named /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalwalsinghamshrine.org/feast-of-our-lady-of-walsingham|title=Upcoming Events: Feast of Our Lady of Walsingham|work=nationalwalsinghamshrine.org|publisher=National Shrine of Our Lady of Walsingham|access-date=11 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200211161331/https://www.nationalwalsinghamshrine.org/feast-of-our-lady-of-walsingham|archive-date=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Campus ministry===\n[[File:Covenant between William & Mary\u2019s Catholic Student Association and Canterbury, 1977.jpg|thumb|150px|Ecumenical covenant signed by Bishop [[Walter Francis Sullivan]] of the Diocese of Richmond and Bishop Coadjutor [[Charles Vach\u00e9]] of the [[Diocese of Southern Virginia]] and representatives from the Catholic Student Association and Canterbury at William & Mary]]\nIn 1865, the College reported a single Catholic student.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scdbwiki.swem.wm.edu/wiki/index.php/Religious_Beliefs_of_Students|title=Religious Beliefs of Students|work=Special Collections Research Center Wiki|publisher=William & Mary Libraries|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref> By 1939, 114 Catholics attended the College or lived in the nearby community.<ref name=Spike40/> As of 2019, an average of 225 students attend Sunday Mass at the Shrine, with an average of 25 students attending daily masses at the Shrine or in the [[Wren Building|Wren chapel]].<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200210204628/https://www.tribecatholic.org/annualreport|url=https://www.tribecatholic.org/annualreport|title=Annual Report|publisher=William & Mary Catholic Campus Ministry|work=tribecatholic.org|access-date=10 February 2020|archive-date=10 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Gibbons Club was founded in 1923, later renamed the [[Newman Center|Newman Club]] after the establishment of the parish.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scdbwiki.swem.wm.edu/wiki/index.php/Gibbons_Club|title=Gibbons Club|work=Special Collections Research Center Wiki|publisher=William & Mary Libraries|access-date=6 February 2020}}</ref> The Newman Club was later renamed to the Catholic Student Association. Alongside their [[Episcopal Church (United States)|Episcopalian]] equivalent, Canterbury, the CSA signed a covenant\u2013committing both organizations to  ecumenical actions\u2013in the Wren Chapel on 24 January 1977. The CSA and Canterbury formerly cooperated in running a chapter of [[Covenant Players]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DaqLdYMaeB0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Camille+Thompson+college+of+William+and+mary&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi20ZmXz8fnAhXPmHIEHXLRABsQ6AEwAXoECAEQAg#v=onepage&q=Camille%20Thompson%20college%20of%20William%20and%20mary&f=false|page=155|last=Thompson|first=Camille|work=College Prowler|title=College of William and Mary: Off the Record|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref> The student ministry was again renamed to its present title, Catholic Campus Ministry, in line with the names of other campus ministries within the Diocese of Richmond.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tribecatholic.org|title=Tribe Catholic|publisher=William & Mary Catholic Campus Ministry|work=tribecatholic.org|access-date=10 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://evangelizerichmond.org/campus/find-a-campus/|title=Find a Campus|publisher=Diocese of Richmond|author=Office of Evangelization|work=evangelizerichmond.org|access-date=11 February 2020}}</ref> The Catholic Student Center, located alongside the Shrine, is colloquially known as the \"Catacombs\" or \"Cats.\"<ref name=Center />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Richmond}}\n{{Catholic Church}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic national shrines in the United States]]\n[[Category:Churches in the Roman Catholic Diocese of Richmond]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Williamsburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Williamsburg, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Williamsburg, Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toAlgonquin(link changed toAlgonquian peoples) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Bede_Catholic_Church_(Williamsburg,_Virginia)"}
