n}}\n| serviceyears  = \n| rank          = [[:ru:\u0413\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b \u0430\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0438 (\u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0421\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0435\u0439 \u0410\u0437\u0438\u0438)|General of the Army]]\n| unit          = \n| battles       = \n| education     = \n| mawards       = \n}}\n'''Gurbanguly M\u00e4likguly\u00fdewi\u00e7 Berdimuhamedow'''{{efn|{{IPA-tk|\u0281\u028a\u027eb\u0251n\u0281\u028a\u02c8l\u026f b\u025b\u027ed\u026fm\u028ax\u0251m\u025b\u02c8do\u03b2|}}}}{{efn|Evidently, the names consist of a series of compounds:{{Original research inline|date=August 2019}}<br/>\n* The given name can be analysed as ''gurban'' ('sacrifice') (cf. Arab.-Pers. \u0642\u0631\u0628\u0627\u0646 ) and ''guly'' (from Pers. \u063a\u0644\u06cc [ghul\u012b], an abbreviated form of Arab.-Pers. \u063a\u0644\u0627\u0645 [ghul\u0101m], 'servant').\n* The patronymic consists of ''m\u00e4lik'' (Arab.-Pers. \u0645\u0644\u06a9 [malik], 'king', 'sovereign', Pers. \u063a\u0644\u06cc [ghul\u012b], and finally the Russian patronymic suffix -\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447).\n* The surname contains three elements: ''berdi'' ('servant', 'slave') (from Pers. \u0628\u0631\u062f\u0647 [bardah]), the name of the Islamic prophet, Muhammad, and Russian -\u043e\u0432 (the common Slavic suffix of origin/family).}}{{efn|or ''Gurbanguly Berdymuhamedov'', ''Berdymukhammedov''; Although '''Gurbanguly M\u00e4likguly\u00fdewi\u00e7 Berdimuhamedow''' is the only Turkmen form, and Turkmen, written with Latin alphabet, is the only official language of Turkmenistan, Western sources generally use the Russian form \"\u0413\u0443\u0440\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0443\u043b\u044b\" or \"\u041a\u0443\u0440\u0431\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0443\u043b\u044b \u041c\u044f\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0433\u0443\u043b\u044b\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c(\u043c)\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432,\" using various transcriptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2006/12/56E64767-9340-464A-8C8E-96FC8E277DE1.html |title=Turkmen Assembly Discussing Political Future|publisher=Rferl.org |date=26 December 2006 |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2006/12/26A1157E-4545-4AAE-998F-F15A08AF29AE.html |title=Acting Turkmen President Cleared To Run In February Election |publisher=Rferl.org |date=27 December 2006|accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2006/12/F02EFA71-93BF-478A-9200-D909ECB87380.html |title=Turkmenistan Registers Presidential Candidates |publisher=Rferl.org |date=28 December 2006 |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/country_profiles/1298497.stm |title=Turkmenistan country profile - Overview |publisher=BBC News |date= |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6213875.stm |title=Asia-Pacific &#124; Turkmen 'heir apparent' emerges |publisher=BBC News |date=28 December 2006 |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Than |first=Krisztina |url=http://today.reuters.com/news/articlenews.aspx?type=worldNews&storyID=2006-12-25T142543Z_01_L25241972_RTRUKOC_0_US-TURKMENISTAN.xml&WTmodLoc=IntNewsHome_C2_worldNews-3 |title=Business & Financial News, Breaking US & International News &#124; Reuters.com |publisher=Today.reuters.com |date=9 February 2009 |accessdate=5 September 2015 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/27/world/asia/27turkmenistan.html|title=Turkmenistan Limits Election to Soviet-Style Slate|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/30/world/asia/30turkmenistan.html?ref=asia|title=Turkmen Exile Urges Interim President to Step Down|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/world/20061226-1210-turkmenistan-election.html |title=Turkmenistan's interim leader crowned as heir apparent to late dictator |publisher=SignOnSanDiego.com |date=26 December 2006 |accessdate=5 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201034509/http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/world/20061226-1210-turkmenistan-election.html |archivedate=1 February 2009 }}</ref>}}{{efn|The English version of the website of the presidency uses a curious mixture of the Turkmen spelling with a transcribed ending: '''Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov'''<ref>[http://turkmenistan.gov.tm/_en/ Turkmenistan: The Golden Age] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417014826/http://turkmenistan.gov.tm/_en/ |date=17 April 2009 }}</ref>}} (born 29 June 1957)<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkmenistan: New President Shows Shades Of 'Turkmenbashi' |url=http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2007/07/553cbfb1-46aa-4757-ae2b-2069350baf5f.html |work=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date=3 July 2007 |accessdate=16 July 2007}}</ref> is a [[Turkmenistan|Turkmen]] politician who has been serving as the [[President of Turkmenistan]] since February 2007. Berdimuhamedow, a [[dentistry|dentist]] by profession, served in the government under President [[Saparmurat Niyazov]] as Minister of Health beginning in 1997 and as Vice-President beginning in 2001. He became Acting President following Niyazov's death on 21 December 2006 and subsequently won the [[2007 Turkmen presidential election|February 2007 presidential election]]. He faced no meaningful opposition in the vote and won by an overwhelming margin (89.23%).<ref name=\"sworn\">{{cite news |title=New Turkmen President Sworn In|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/1074693.html |work=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date=14 February 2007 |accessdate=6 March 2007 }}</ref> In the [[2012 Turkmenistani presidential election|February 2012 presidential election]], he was re-elected with 97% of the vote. In the [[2017 Turkmenistani presidential election|February 2017 presidential election]], he was re-elected to a third term with 97.69% of the votes.<ref>[http://www.rferl.org/a/berdymukhammedov-turkmenistan-presidential-election/28304657.html Turkmen President Extends Rule In Tightly Controlled Vote] [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]] (www.rferl.org). 13 February 2017. Retrieved on 24 February 2017.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/world/2012-02/17/c_131416863.htm|title=Turkmen president sworn in for second term|work=xinhuanet.com}}</ref>\n\nAs with his predecessor, a [[Cult of personality|personality cult]] is promoted around Berdimuhamedow. According to [[Human Rights Watch]], Berdimuhamedow, his relatives, and his associates possess unlimited power and exercise [[Totalitarianism|total control over all aspects of public life]].<ref name=\"MyUser_Hrw.org_January_28_2015c\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2014/country-chapters/turkmenistan |title=World Report 2014: Turkmenistan |newspaper=Hrw.org |date=  |author= |accessdate= 28 January 2015}}</ref> He uses the honorific title '''Arkadag''', meaning \"protector\" in the [[Turkmen language]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://enews.fergananews.com/news.php?id=2003&print=1 |title=Turkmenistan: President Gurbanguly Berdymukhammedov is awarded the status of Arkadag \u2013 protector - Ferghana Information agency, Moscow |publisher=Enews.fergananews.com |date= |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nBerdimuhamedow was born on 29 June 1957 in [[Babarap]], in what is now the [[Geok Tepe]] ''etrap'' (\"district\") of [[Ahal Province]], to [[:ru:\u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432, \u041c\u044f\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0433\u0443\u043b\u044b \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|M\u00e4likguly Berdimuhamedowi\u00e7 Berdimuhamedow]] and Ogulabat Ata\u00fdewna K\u00fcrr\u00e4\u00fdewa.<ref name=\"arhyw\" /> He is the only son in a family of six children. Berdimuhammedow\u2019s father worked as a senior Interior Ministry officer in a prison guard detachment. He retired as a Colonel of police.<ref name=\"theguardian cables\">[https://amp.theguardian.com/world/us-embassy-cables-documents/240618 US embassy cables: Turkmenistan president 'not a very bright guy'], ''Theguardian.com'', 2 December 2010</ref> Berdimuhammedow graduated from the [[Turkmen State Medical Institute]] in 1979 and entered a career in dentistry.<ref name=\"guardian 2008\">{{cite news|title=And finally... how the march of a lone cockroach put 30 people out of work|publisher = The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/feb/22/television| author=Luke Harding|date=22 February 2008|accessdate=22 February 2008}}</ref> He also received a PhD in medical sciences in [[Moscow]].<ref name=\"guardian 2008\"/> By 1992 he had become part of the dentistry faculty at the Medical Institute.\n\nIn 1995, during the rule of [[Saparmurat Niyazov]], Berdimuhamedow became head of the dentistry center of the Ministry of Health and Medical Industry.<ref name=\"bbc profile\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6346185.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Asia-Pacific - Profile: Kurbanguly Berdymukhamedov|work=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> He was appointed to the government as Minister of Health in 1997, and he was additionally appointed as Deputy Chairman of the Cabinet of Ministers (also referred to as [[Deputy Prime Minister]], despite the lack of a Prime Ministerial post in Turkmenistan), a post akin to that of a Vice-President, in 2001.<ref>[http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2006/12/3F7885AA-B6AA-4028-A29C-3CF882FC2FA0.html \"Turkmenistan: Change Of Leadership Presents Many Dangers\"], Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberties, 22 December 2006.</ref><ref>[http://www.press-uz.info/ru/content.scm?topicId=2633&contentId=37772 Press-Uz.info] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930020824/http://www.press-uz.info/ru/content.scm?topicId=2633&contentId=37772 |date=30 September 2007 }}, 22 December 2006 (in [[Russian language|Russian]]).</ref> In April 2004, Niyazov suspended Berdimuhamedow's salary for three months because healthcare workers were not being paid.<ref name=\"bbc profile\"/>\n\n[[File:Vladimir Putin in Turkmenistan 23-24 April 2002-1.jpg|thumb|Berdimuhamedow with Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] at [[Ashgabat International Airport|Ashgabat Airport]].]]\n\nThe Health Ministry was responsible for carrying out Niyazov's notorious order to close all hospitals outside of the capital city and major regional towns in 2005.<ref>[http://web.amnesty.org/library/Index/ENGEUR610012005?open&of=ENG-348 \"Turkmenistan: President announces large-scale closure of hospitals\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061225003607/http://web.amnesty.org/library/Index/ENGEUR610012005?open&of=ENG-348 |date=25 December 2006 }}, Amnesty International, 24 March 2005.</ref>\n\n==President of Turkmenistan==\n[[File:Dmitry Medvedev in Turkmenistan 13 September 2009-1.jpg|thumb|With [[President of Russia|President]] [[Dmitry Medvedev]] and [[President of Kazakhstan]] [[Nursultan Nazarbayev]]]]\n\nFollowing Niyazov's death in December 2006, the [[State Security Council of Turkmenistan]] appointed Berdimuhamedow as acting president.<ref>[http://www.HVBhlsBDVlchZBDLvbSLvlbl/cis/20061221/57476457.html] {{dead link|date=September 2015}}</ref> The Council stated in its announcement that [[\u00d6wezgeldi Ata\u00fdew]], who, as the Chairman of the [[Assembly of Turkmenistan]] was to become the acting president, was not appointed \"in view of the fact that the prosecutor-general had instituted criminal proceedings against him\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Turkmen Dpty PM Berdymukhammedov appointed acting president|url=http://www.itarass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=11104815|publisher=[[ITAR-TASS]]|date=21 December 2006}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Official welcome ceremony was held for President of Turkmenistan Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow.jpg|thumb|150px|Berdimuhamedow with [[President of Azerbaijan]] [[Ilham Aliyev]].]]\n[[File:Official visit of the President to Turkmenistan 01.jpg|thumb|150px|Berdimuhamedow with [[Petro Poroshenko]].]]\n\nArticle 60 of the Turkmen Constitution stipulated that the acting president \"may not stand for election to the Presidency\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislationline.org/upload/legislations/4f/56/33fa31942510288eb01ea3a1508a.pdf|title=Legislationline.|work=legislationline.org|df=}}{{dead link|date=July 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> which would have barred Berdimuhamedow from running in the 2007 presidential elections. However, on 24 December 2006, the [[People's Council of Turkmenistan|People's Council]] voted to remove this provision, making him eligible for the election as one of the six chosen candidates, all members of the [[Democratic Party of Turkmenistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6359569.stm |title=Asia-Pacific &#124; New Turkmen leader is inaugurated |publisher=BBC News |date=14 February 2007 |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref> Berdimuhamedov was supported by the political elite,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.interfax.ru/e/B/politics/28.html?id_issue=11654021|title=Acting leader proposed as candidate for Turkmen president|agency=[[Interfax]]|date=26 December 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930224910/http://www.interfax.ru/e/B/politics/28.html?id_issue=11654021 |archivedate=30 September 2007 }}</ref> and the official results showed him as winning 89% of the vote.<ref name=\"sworn\" /><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070213014806/http://www.voanews.com/english/2007-02-11-voa13.cfm Turkmenistan Votes for Presidential Successor], ''Voanews.com'', 11 February 2007</ref>\n\nIn his first presidential trip abroad, Berdimuhamedov visited [[Saudi Arabia]] in mid-April 2007. There he performed the [[Umrah]] pilgrimage and met with [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|King Abdullah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cacianalyst.org/newsite/?q=node/4594/print|title=BERDYMUKHAMMEDOV BURNISHES MUSLIM CREDENTIALS ON VISIT TO SAUDI ARABIA|work=cacianalyst.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926234552/http://www.cacianalyst.org/newsite/?q=node%2F4594%2Fprint|archivedate=26 September 2007}}</ref> He then visited [[Russia]] and President [[Vladimir Putin]] at the end of the same month.\n\n[[File:Gurbanguly Berdimuhammedov with Obamas.jpg|thumb|Berdimuhamedow with [[President of the United States|US President]] [[Barack Obama]] and [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Michelle Obama]]]]\n[[File:Third GECF summit in Tehran 41.jpg|thumb|Berdimuhamedow with Iranian President [[Hassan Rouhani]] during the [[Third GECF summit]]]]\n\nAfter taking office, Berdimuhamedow reversed several of Niyazov's more eccentric policies. Internet caf\u00e9s offering free and uncensored web access opened in [[Ashgabat]],<ref>{{cite news \n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | agency = Associated Press\n  | title = A crack in the isolation of Turkmenistan: Internet cafes\n  | work =\n  | pages =\n  | publisher = USA Today\n  | date = 16 February 2007\n  | url = https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2007-02-16-turkmenistan_x.htm\n  | accessdate = 26 April 2007 }}\n</ref> compulsory education was extended from nine to ten years and classes in sports and foreign languages were re-introduced into the curriculum, and the government announced plans to open several specialised schools for the arts.<ref>{{cite news \n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = 1 \u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u043b\u044f \u0432 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u043e\u044e\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044b \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430\n  | work =\n  | pages =\n  | publisher = G\u00fcndogar\n  | date = 21 February 2007\n  | url = http://www.gundogar.org/?022500000000000000011062007020000#3922\n  | accessdate = 26 April 2007|language=ru}}\n</ref> President Berdimuhamedow has called for reform of education, health care and pension systems, and government officials of non-Turkmen ethnic origin who had been sacked by Niyazov were allowed to return to work.<ref>{{cite news\n |author      = Leila\n |title       = Internet in Turkmenistan: A sign of hope?\n |publisher   = New Eurasia\n |date        = 20 February 2007\n |url         = http://turkmenistan.neweurasia.net/?p=176\n |accessdate  = 26 April 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070516173113/http://turkmenistan.neweurasia.net/?p=176\n |archivedate = 16 May 2007\n}}\n</ref> He also restored the pensions of 100,000 elderly people whose pensions Niyazov had slashed in the face of an unspecified budget crisis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/03/19/asia/AS-GEN-Turkmenistan-Pensions.php|title=New Turkmen president restores pensions to more than 100,000|periodical=[[International Herald Tribune]]|date=19 March 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013155211/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/03/19/asia/AS-GEN-Turkmenistan-Pensions.php |archivedate=13 October 2008 }}</ref> Later on, he reopened the Turkmen Academy of Sciences, which had been closed by Niyazov.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gundogar.org/?024100000000000000011062007060000#4470|title=\u0413\u0443\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0433\u0430\u0440 :: NEWS|work=Gundogar.org|accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, he was reelected to a third term as President of Turkmenistan (seven-year term) with nearly 98% of the votes in his favor and with an eligible voter turnout of 97%.<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/02/gurbanguly-berdymukhamedov-wins-poll-98-vote-170213060136393.html Gurbanguly Berdymukhamedov wins poll with 98% of vote], ''Aljazeera.com'', 13 February 2017 \"Turkmenistan's ruling leader Gurbanguly Berdymukhamedov bagged a fresh seven-year term with nearly 98 percent of a weakly contested vote, electoral officials following a preliminary count said. The election commission claimed at a news conference on Monday, in the capital Ashgabat, a turnout of more than 97 percent for the poll,\"</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/turkmen-president-elected-98-percent-of-vote/3722818.html|title=Turkmen President Re-elected with 98 Percent of Vote|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|date=13 February 2017|accessdate=8 July 2019|quote=The president of Turkmenistan won re-election with nearly 98 percent of the votes, the country\u2019s election commission reported. President Gurbanguly Berdymukhamedov was elected to a third term which will last for seven years. He was first elected president in 2006. The election results were announced Sunday night by the Central Asian nation\u2019s election commission. The commission said 97 percent of eligible voters turned out to vote.}}</ref> In October 2017, he offered a top Turkmen-bred variety of the Central Asian shepherd dog to [[Vladimir Putin]].<ref>Tim Lister, [https://edition.cnn.com/2017/10/11/world/russia-putin-birthday-puppy-trnd/index.html Pup-lover Putin gifted new dog for birthday], ''CNN'', 12 October 2017</ref>\n\nHe was reelected as president of the [[National Olympic Committee of Turkmenistan]] on 22 April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|date=22 April 2018|url= http://tdh.gov.tm/news/articles.aspx&article12456&cat30|title=President Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov is re-elected the Head of National Olympic Committee |publisher=[[Turkmenistan State News Agency]]|access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\n\n===Accusations of totalitarianism===\n{{see|Human rights in Turkmenistan}}\n[[File:Gurbanguly-Berdimuhamedow-On-Horse.JPG|thumb|Image of Berdimuhamedow, on display outside the national horse-racing ground in Ashgabat, Turkmenistan]]\n{{external media\n| align = right\n| video1  = [https://www.rferl.org/a/our-hero-lavish-praise-for-turkmen-president-s-cutbacks/29521371.html Turkmenistan's president announces end of free gas, electricity, water, and salt]\n| video2  = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U6I6RtxTpGA Turkmen president visits local village]\n}}\n\nUpon taking office, Berdimuhamedow eased travel restrictions and reopened libraries in rural areas. He also took steps to curb Niyazov's extensive [[Cult of personality|personality cult]]. He called for an end to the elaborate pageants of music and dancing that formerly greeted the president on his arrival anywhere, and said that the Turkmen \"sacred oath\", part of which states that the speaker's tongue should shrivel if he ever speaks ill of Turkmenistan or its president, should not be recited multiple times a day but reserved for \"special occasions.\"<ref>{{cite news \n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = Turkmenistan moves to reduce cult\n  | work =\n  | pages =\n  | publisher = MWC News\n  | date = 10 March 2007\n  | url = http://mwcnews.net/content/view/13117/195/\n  | accessdate = 26 April 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070313203413/http://mwcnews.net/content/view/13117/195/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 13 March 2007}}\n</ref> He also gave up his right to rename any landmarks, institutions, or cities,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2007/03/4649a16c-291d-4855-bc62-4c7018304bff.html|title=Turkmenistan Restricts Presidential Prerogatives|work=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref> restored the traditional names of the months of the year and days of the week (Niyazov had renamed them after himself and his mother, among other things),<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7365346.stm | work=BBC News | title=Turkmen go back to old calendar | date=24 April 2008 | accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref> and announced plans to move the infamous [[Neutrality Monument|gold rotating statue]] of Niyazov from Ashgabat's central square.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7382512.stm | work=BBC News | title=Ex-Turkmen leader's statue moved | date=3 May 2008 | accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref> However, he explicitly ruled out any move toward Western-style democracy.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7155476.stm | work=BBC News | title=Fresh optimism in Turkmenistan | date=21 December 2007 | accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, he dismissed [[Akmyrat Rejepow]], the longtime chief of the presidential security detail and one of the main proponents of Niyazov's personality cult.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurasianet.org/departments/insight/articles/pp051607.shtml |title=Turkmenistan: New President Sacks Long-Serving Security Chief |publisher=EurasiaNet.org |date=15 May 2007 |accessdate=5 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924021545/http://www.eurasianet.org/departments/insight/articles/pp051607.shtml |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2011, he sang a song on a video posted to [[YouTube]].<ref>[https://www.rferl.org/a/chaikhana_talented_mr_berdymukhammedov/24298760.html The Talented Mr. Berdymukhammedov], ''Rferl.org'', 16 August 2011</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, [[Jennifer Lopez]] publicly apologized for singing ''Happy birthday!'' to Berdimuhamedow during a sponsored concert, stating she was not aware of the [[human rights]] issues in Turkmenistan prior to the show.<ref>Jared Anderson, [https://www.cnbc.com/id/100860190 Jennifer Lopez Apologizes for Celebrating Resource-Rich Dictator], ''Cnbc.com'', 2 July 2013</ref> In August 2013, Berdimuhamedow suspended his Democratic Party of Turkmenistan membership for the duration of his presidency, ostensibly to remain \"above partisan politics\" and \"promote a multiparty system.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2013/08/18/world/turkmen-president-quits-top-party/#.Uhc6c5LiH4g|title=Turkmen president quits top party|work=The Japan Times}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, he fell off his horse during a race. The fall was censored on TV but leaked online.<ref>[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/01/gurbanguly-berdymukhamedov-turkmenistan-president-falls-off-horse-video_n_3191625.html Gurbanguly Berdymukhamedov, Turkmenistan President, Falls Off Horse During Race (VIDEO)], ''Huffingtonpost.com'', 6 December 2017</ref> On 11 August 2019, an episode of [[HBO]]'s ''[[Last Week Tonight with John Oliver]]'' featured two clips of the incident. This was part of a long piece satirising the dictator, culminating in the unveiling of a 55 sq meter marble cake decorated with a giant image of the president falling off the horse.\n\nIn 2015, a golden statue of Berdimuhamedow riding a horse atop a white-marble cliff was erected in Ashgabat.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/may/25/horse-turkmenistan-president-statute-berdymukhamedov  | work=The Guardian | title=A horse, a horse \u2026 Turkmenistan president honours himself with statue | date=25 May 2015 | accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref><ref>Adam Taylor, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2015/05/25/turkmenistans-leader-infamous-for-falling-off-a-horse-unveils-a-giant-statue-of-himself-riding-a-horse/ Turkmenistan\u2019s leader, infamous for falling off a horse, unveils a giant statue of himself riding a horse], ''Washingtonpost.com'', 25 May 2015</ref>\n\nAccording to international observers, Berdimuhamedow now leads \"one of the most oppressive\" and \"closed\" regimes in the world. [[Freedom House]] has consistently placed Turkmenistan near the bottom of its [[Freedom in the World]] rankings since Berdimuhamedow took office; in 2017, the country was one of 11 with the lowest aggregate scores for political and civil rights.<ref>[https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-world/freedom-world-2017 Freedom in the World 2017]</ref> [[Human Rights Watch]] noted that Berdimuhamedow not only has complete control over public life, but presides over a regime that does not tolerate \"alternative political or religious expression\" and has complete control over the media.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2017/country-chapters/turkmenistan |title=World Report 2017: Turkmenistan |publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]] |date=  |author= |accessdate= 30 June 2017}}</ref> [[Reporters Without Borders]] has ranked Turkmenistan near the bottom of its [[Press Freedom Index]] for most of Berdimuhamedow's tenure. In 2017, RWB ranked Turkmenistan 178th out of 180 countries surveyed, ahead of [[Eritrea]] and [[North Korea]]. RSF noted that internet access is heavily censored in Turkmenistan, and that [[satellite dish]]es have been removed by government officials.<ref>[https://rsf.org/en/turkmenistan Turkmenistan] at 2017 [[Press Freedom Index]]</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, the Turkmenistan Parliament abolished term limits for the presidency, which allowed Berdimuhamedow to run for a third term.<ref>Damien Sharkov, [https://www.newsweek.com/turkmenistan-president-gurbanguly-berdimuhamedov-indefinite-rule-498347 Turkmenistan votes to allow president rule indefinitely], ''Newsweek.com'', 14 September 2016</ref>\nIn July 2018, he appeared in a [[rap]] video with his grandson. He had previously lifted weights on camera, and also acted as [[DJ]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2018/jul/11/turkmenistans-president-performs-in-rap-video-with-his-grandson-video Turkmenistan's president performs in rap video with his grandson \u2013 video], ''Theguardian.com'', 11 July 2018</ref>\n\nBy decree of Berdymuhamedov in January 2019, the government will gradually end state funding of the [[Academy of Sciences of Turkmenistan]]; it will be phased out in three years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/turkmenistan-to-cut-state-funding-for-science/2019/01/30/76e9528c-24c5-11e9-b5b4-1d18dfb7b084_story.html?utm_term=.4cc850804028|title=Turkmenistan to cut state funding for science|publisher=The Washington Post|date=2019-01-30|accessdate=2019-08-18}}{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n=== Violation of individual rights ===\nThe ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' magazine named Berdimuhamedow the 5th of the 23 worst dictators in the world. In the Press Freedom Index (Reporters Without Borders), Turkmenistan ranks 176 out of 178.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.obozrevatel.com/news/2010/9/20/391886.htm|title=\u0412 \u0440\u0435\u0439\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0433 \u0445\u0443\u0434\u0448\u0438\u0445 \u0434\u0438\u043a\u0442\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0430\u043b\u043e \u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435 \u0438\u0437 \u0421\u041d\u0413|website=\u041f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0430|language=ru|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n\nTurkmenistan leads in the number of political prisoners from all countries of the former Soviet Union.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.osce.org/odihr/124153?download=true|title=2014 OSCE Human Dimension Implementation Meeting, Working Session 5, Wednesday 24 September 2014: Rule of Law 2}}</ref>\n\n=== Corruption ===\nThe country's economy is under total state control. Numerous attempts to attract foreign investors into the country often end in lawsuits in international courts. In 2018, the International Center for the Settlement of Investment Disputes (arbitration, part of the World Bank group of organizations) received claims against Turkmenistan from Sece In\u015faat (Turkey) and investment company Unionmatex Industrieanlagen GmbH (Germany).\n\nIn 2019, the Belarusian construction company Belgorkhimprom also filed a similar claim with the court, to which Turkmenistan should pay about $200 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hronikatm.com/2019/02/turkmenhimiya-zadolzhala-belgorhimpromu-bolee-150-mln-za-stroitelstvo-garlykoskogo-gok/|title=\"\u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0445\u0438\u043c\u0438\u044f\" \u0437\u0430\u0434\u043e\u043b\u0436\u0430\u043b\u0430 \"\u0411\u0435\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0445\u0438\u043c\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0443\" \u0431\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0435 $150 \u043c\u043b\u043d \u0437\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0413\u0430\u0440\u043b\u044b\u043a\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0413\u041e\u041a\u0425\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430|last=Editor|date=2019-02-01|website=\u0425\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430|language=ru-RU|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tsn.life/ad-investora-neskolko-realnyx-istorij-lyudej-i-kompanij-reshivshixsya-vlozhit-dengi-v-turkmenistan/|title=\u0410\u0434 \u0438\u043d\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430. \u041d\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u0440\u0435\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0435\u0439 \u0438 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439, \u0440\u0435\u0448\u0438\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0445\u0441\u044f \u0432\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0434\u0435\u043d\u044c\u0433\u0438 \u0432 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d}}</ref>\n\nInvestors talk about discrimination against the Turkmen authorities, politicized bureaucracy, and a high level of corruption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://infopressa.com/2019/05/07/kak-tyrkmenistan-kidaia-investorov-podtverjdaet-svoi-podvalnye-indeksy/|title=\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d, \u043a\u0438\u0434\u0430\u044f \u0438\u043d\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432, \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0434\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0432\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0438\u043d\u0434\u0435\u043a\u0441\u044b {{!}} http://infopressa.com|language=ru-RU|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n\nIn the Transparency International Corruption Perception Index, Turkmenistan ranked 161 among 180 countries in 2018. This is the lowest rating among countries in Eastern Europe and Central Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eadaily.com/ru/news/2018/02/22/transparency-international-turkmeniya-lidiruet-v-mirovom-reytinge-korrupcii|title=Transparency International: \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043b\u0438\u0434\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0435\u0439\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0440\u0443\u043f\u0446\u0438\u0438|website=EADaily|language=ru|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.transparency.org/cpi2018|title=Corruption Perceptions Index 2018|last=e.V|first=Transparency International|website=transparency.org|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Turkmenistan ranked 164th among 180 countries in the ranking of economic freedom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heritage.org/index/|title=Index of Economic Freedom: Promoting Economic Opportunity and Prosperity by Country|website=heritage.org|language=en|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Domestic awards===\n* 1994 \u2013 [[Star of President Order]]\n\n===Foreign awards===\n[[File:The Prime Minister, Shri Narendra Modi presents the President of Turkmenistan, Mr. Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov a specially handcrafted horse saddle, in Ashgabat, Turkmenistan on July 11, 2015.jpg|thumb|A specially handcrafted [[horse saddle]] given to him as a gift from [[Indian Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] in July 2015.]]\n* 2007 \u2013 {{Flag|United Arab Emirates}}: [[Order of Zayed]]{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n* 2007 \u2013 {{Flag|Uzbekistan}}: [[Order of Distinguished Service (Uzbekistan)|Order of Distinguished Service]]{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n* 2008 \u2013 {{Flag|Kazakhstan}}: [[Medal \"10 years of Astana\"]]{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n* 2010 \u2013 {{Flag|Tajikistan}}: [[Order of Ismoili Somoni]]{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n* 2011 \u2013 {{Flag|Bahrain}}: [[Order of Sheikh Isa bin Salman Al Khalifa]]{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n* 2012 \u2013 {{Flag|Turkey}}: First Class of the [[Order of the State of Republic of Turkey]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tccb.gov.tr/konuk-devlet-baskanlari/255/82242/turkmenistan.html|title= Official visit of Turkmenistan|publisher=[[\u00c7ankaya K\u00f6\u015fk\u00fc|Presidency of Republic of Turkey]]|date=29 February 2012|accessdate=25 February 2015}}</ref>\n* 2013 \u2013 {{Flag|Serbia}}: Order of the Republic of Serbia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blic.rs/Vesti/Politika/476971/Nikolic-ordenja-deli-u-tri-smene|title=Blic Online - Nikoli\u0107 ordenja deli u tri smene|work=Blic Online}}</ref>\n* 2016, 2017 \u2013 {{Flag|Moldova}}: [[Order of the Republic (Moldova)]]\n* 2017 \u2013 {{Flag|Russia}}: [[Order of Alexander Nevsky]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/transcripts/55753|title=Press statements following Russia-Turkmenistan talks|work=President of Russia|access-date=2 October 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n* 2017 \u2013 {{Flag|Russia}}: [[Order of Dyslyk]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.akipress.com/news:608331&#|title=AKIpress News Agency|website=m.akipress.com|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAccording to a [[Diplomatic cable|cable]] from the U.S. embassy in Ashgabat, Berdimuhamedow is married and has three daughters and one son. One of his sons-in-law, Yhlasgeldi Amanov, headed the Turkmen State Agency for Management and Use of Hydrocarbon Resources in London, was later assigned to the Turkmenistan Embassies in Berlin and London, and as of 23 November 2019 was Turkmenistan's consul general in Dubai.<ref name=dubai>{{cite news|url=https://www.hronikatm.com/2019/11/uae-consulate/|title=\u0412 \u0414\u0443\u0431\u0430\u0435 \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u043b\u043e\u0441\u044c \u0442\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e, \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b \u0437\u044f\u0442\u044c \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430|language=Russian|date=24 November 2019|publisher=\u0425\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430}}</ref>  The other son-in-law is also a diplomat, with a prior posting in Paris, but who is currently assigned to Brussels.<ref name=\"theguardian cables\"/>\n\nAccording to the same leaked cables, Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow  has a mistress, Marina, a Russian nurse that he supposedly met earlier in his dentist career. They have a 14-year old daughter together. Berdimuhamedow's wife has been living in London since 2007.<ref name=\"theguardian cables\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/cable/2009/12/09ASHGABAT1633.html|title=Cable Viewer|work=wikileaks.org}}</ref>\n\nHis son, [[Serdar Berdimuhamedow]], is a lieutenant colonel in the [[Armed Forces of Turkmenistan|Armed Forces]].<ref>[https://rus.azattyq.org/amp/28823232.html \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043b \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0441\u044b\u043d\u0430 \u043c\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044c\u044e \u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0435\u0433\u043e \u043e\u0442\u0446\u0430], ''Azattyq.com'', 30 October 2017</ref>  Serdar was appointed governor of Ahal velayat (province) in June 2019.<ref name=ahalhakim>{{cite news|url=https://www.hronikatm.com/2019/06/monarchy/|title=\u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0438\u043b \u0441\u044b\u043d\u0430 \u0445\u044f\u043a\u0438\u043c\u043e\u043c \u0410\u0445\u0430\u043b\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432\u0435\u043b\u0430\u044f\u0442\u0430|language=Russian|date=17 June 2019|publisher=\u0425\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430}}</ref>\n\nAt least three of Berdimuhamedow's grandchildren study in Switzerland: Kerimguly, Ogulb\u00e4bek, and A\u00fdg\u00fcl.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://turkmen.news/news/vnuk-berdymuhamedova-obuchaetsya-v-shvejtsarii/|title=\u0412\u043d\u0443\u043a\u0438 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u0443\u0447\u0430\u044e\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0432 \u044d\u043b\u0438\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0435 \u0432 \u0428\u0432\u0435\u0439\u0446\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0438 (\u043e\u0431\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043e)|date=30 Jan 2020|publisher=turkmen.news}}</ref>\n\nHis grandfather, Berdimuhamed Annayev, was a veteran of the [[Great Patriotic War]] and since 2018, a posthumous recipient of the Russian [[Order of Honour (Russia)|Order of Honour]].<ref>Sapar Muradov, [http://orient.tm/en/2018/09/27/10427.html Military school named after Berdimuhamed Annayev receives the Medal of Honour, which was awarded to the grandfather of President of Turkmenistan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928201030/http://orient.tm/en/2018/09/27/10427.html |date=28 September 2018 }}, ''Orient.tm'', 27 September 2018</ref>  According to a biography of Berdimuhamedow's father published in 2012, Berdimuhamedow has five sisters: Durdynabat (born 1960), Gulnabat (born 1962), M\u00e4hri (born 1964), Guljamal (born 1969), and Oguljamal (born 1974).<ref name=\"arhyw\">{{cite book |title=Watany\u0148 Wepaly Ogly|author=T\u00fcrkmenistany\u0148 Prezidentini\u0148 Arhiw gaznasy|date=2012|publisher=T\u00fcrkmen d\u00f6wlet ne\u015fir\u00fdat gullugy|location=Ashgabat}}</ref>\n\nDuring his spare time from being President, from his dentistry career and from his political career, he writes books that are popular in [[Turkmenistan]] according to Turkmen propaganda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://austria.tmembassy.gov.tm/en/news/5170|title=BOOKS OF THE PRESIDENT OF TURKMENISTAN - WINNERS OF THE INTERNATIONAL PUBLISHING CONTEST {{!}} VIENNA, REPUBLIC OF AUSTRIA - EMBASSY OF TURKMENISTAN|website=austria.tmembassy.gov.tm|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ahal-teke.org/en/New-Book-vHeavenly-Beautyv-by-President-of-Turkmenistan-Gurbanguly-Berdimuhamedov-p29.html|title=New Book \"Heavenly Beauty\" by President of Turkmenistan Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov {{!}} ahat-teke.org|website=ahal-teke.org|language=en|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://turkmenpetroleum.com/en/2017/07/04/the-book-dedicated-to-the-60th-anniversary-of-president-gurbanguly-berdimuhamedov-was-published/|title=The book dedicated to the 60th anniversary of President Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov was published \u2013 tpetroleum|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref><ref>https://en.hronikatm.com/2016/03/turkmenistan-president-lauds-tea-drinking-in-new-book/</ref> Aside from writing books, he is known for writing songs, DJing and engaging in health activities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2018/jul/11/turkmenistans-president-performs-in-rap-video-with-his-grandson-video|title=Turkmenistan's president performs in rap video with his grandson \u2013 video|last=Turkmenistan|first=Source: Chronicle of|date=2018-07-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Health===\nOn July 20, 2019, the [[YouTube]] channel of a Turkmen opposition media outlet announced that Berdimuhamedow had reportedly died while on holiday at the age of 61. He was said to have been on leave since July 15. These reports were published by multiple Russian media outlets on the next day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://govoritmoskva.ru/news/205038/?print=1|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441-\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0423\u0437\u0431\u0435\u043a\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0434\u0438\u043b\u0430, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u043b\u0438\u0434\u0435\u0440 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0436\u0438\u0432|website=govoritmoskva.ru|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref><ref name=\"report\">{{cite web |url=https://gazeta.ru/politics/news/2019/07/21/n_13242091.shtml |title=\u0423\u043c\u0435\u0440 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0413\u0443\u0440\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0443\u043b\u044b \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432, \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0421\u041c\u0418 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721141702/https://m.gazeta.ru/politics/news/2019/07/21/n_13242091.shtml |archive-date=21 July 2019 |date=21 July 2019 |accessdate=21 July 2019 |work=gazeta.ru |language=ru }}</ref> The Turkmen Ambassador to Kyrgyzstan, Shadurdy Mereov, and the Kyrgyz Ministry of Foreign Affairs denied these claims on 21 July. According to The Chronicle of Turkmenistan, Berdimuhamedow went to [[Germany]] because his mother was receiving medical treatment there, and her condition was critical.<ref name=\"mereov\">{{cite web |url=https://m.akipress.com/news:622368/ |title=Embassy of Turkmenistan refutes media reports about death of Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov |date=21 July 2019 |accessdate=21 July 2019 |work=Akipress.com }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Politics of Turkmenistan]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow}}\n{{Wikiquote|Gurbanguly Berdimuhammedov}}\n* [http://turkmenistan.gov.tm/_eng/ Presidency's official website]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/gmberdimuhamedow/ Berdimuhamedow's Instagram Page]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Orazgeldi A\u00fddogdyew]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Vice-President of Turkmenistan|years=2001\u20132007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ra\u015fit Meredow]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Saparmurat Niyazov]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Turkmenistan]]|years=2007\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Heads of government of Turkmenistan}}\n{{Prime Ministers of Turkmenistan}}\n{{Current ECO Leaders}}\n{{Current CIS Leaders}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berdimuhamedov, Gurbanguly}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party of Turkmenistan politicians]]\n[[Category:Ethnic Turkmen people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Turkmenistan]]\n[[Category:Vice-Presidents of Turkmenistan]]\n[[Category:Turkmenistan dentists]]\n[[Category:Turkmenistan Muslims]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Republic (Serbia)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Ismoili Somoni]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Alexander Nevsky]]\n[[Category:Turkmenistani generals]]\n[[Category:Turkmenistan writers]]\n[[Category:Turkmenistan musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Expand Russian|topic=bio|\u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432, \u0413\u0443\u0440\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0443\u043b\u044b \u041c\u044f\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0433\u0443\u043b\u044b\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447|date=February 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific_prefix = Arkadag\n| name = Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow\n| image = File:Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow (2017-10-02) 02.jpg\n| caption = Berdimuhamedow in 2017\n| office = 2nd [[President of Turkmenistan]]\n| term_start = 14 February 2007 <br />{{small|Acting: 21 December 2006 \u2013 14 February 2007}}\n| term_end = \n| predecessor = [[Saparmurat Niyazov]]\n| successor = \n| vicepresident = [[Ra\u015fit Meredow]]\n| office1 = Leader of the [[Democratic Party of Turkmenistan|Democratic Party]]\n| term_start1 = 21 December 2006\n| term_end1 = 18 August 2013<br />{{small|Acting: 21 December 2006 \u2013 4 August 2007}}\n| predecessor1 = [[Saparmurat Niyazov]]\n| successor1 = [[Kasymguly Babaev]]\n| office2 = [[Vice President of Turkmenistan|First Vice President of Turkmenistan]]\n| president2 = [[Saparmurat Niyazov]]\n| term_start2 = 1 March 2001\n| term_end2 = 14 February 2007\n| predecessor2 = [[Orazgeldi A\u00fddogdyew]]\n| successor2 = [[Ra\u015fit Meredow]]\n| birth_name = Gurbanguly M\u00e4likguly\u00fdewi\u00e7 Berdimuhamedow\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1957|6|29|df=n}}\n| birth_place = [[Ahal Region|Babarap]], [[Turkmen Soviet Socialist Republic|Turkmen SSR]], [[Soviet Union]]\n| party = [[Independent politician|Independent]] {{small|(2013\u2013present)}}\n| otherparty = [[Democratic Party of Turkmenistan|Democratic]] {{small|(before 2013)}}\n| alma_mater = [[Turkmen State Medical Institute]]\n| children = 4, including [[Serdar Berdimuhamedow|Serdar]]\n| spouse = Ogulgerek Berdimuhamedova\n| allegiance    = {{flag|Turkmenistan}}\n| branch        = {{army|Turkmenistan}}\n| serviceyears  = \n| rank          = [[:ru:\u0413\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b \u0430\u0440\u043c\u0438\u0438 (\u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430 \u0421\u0440\u0435\u0434\u043d\u0435\u0439 \u0410\u0437\u0438\u0438)|General of the Army]]\n| unit          = \n| battles       = \n| education     = \n| mawards       = \n}}\n'''Gurbanguly M\u00e4likguly\u00fdewi\u00e7 Berdimuhamedow'''{{efn|{{IPA-tk|\u0281\u028a\u027eb\u0251n\u0281\u028a\u02c8l\u026f b\u025b\u027ed\u026fm\u028ax\u0251m\u025b\u02c8do\u03b2|}}}}{{efn|Evidently, the names consist of a series of compounds:{{Original research inline|date=August 2019}}<br/>\n* The given name can be analysed as ''gurban'' ('sacrifice') (cf. Arab.-Pers. \u0642\u0631\u0628\u0627\u0646 ) and ''guly'' (from Pers. \u063a\u0644\u06cc [ghul\u012b], an abbreviated form of Arab.-Pers. \u063a\u0644\u0627\u0645 [ghul\u0101m], 'servant').\n* The patronymic consists of ''m\u00e4lik'' (Arab.-Pers. \u0645\u0644\u06a9 [malik], 'king', 'sovereign', Pers. \u063a\u0644\u06cc [ghul\u012b], and finally the Russian patronymic suffix -\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447).\n* The surname contains three elements: ''berdi'' ('servant', 'slave') (from Pers. \u0628\u0631\u062f\u0647 [bardah]), the name of the Islamic prophet, Muhammad, and Russian -\u043e\u0432 (the common Slavic suffix of origin/family).}}{{efn|or ''Gurbanguly Berdymuhamedov'', ''Berdymukhammedov''; Although '''Gurbanguly M\u00e4likguly\u00fdewi\u00e7 Berdimuhamedow''' is the only Turkmen form, and Turkmen, written with Latin alphabet, is the only official language of Turkmenistan, Western sources generally use the Russian form \"\u0413\u0443\u0440\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0443\u043b\u044b\" or \"\u041a\u0443\u0440\u0431\u0430\u043d\u043a\u0443\u043b\u044b \u041c\u044f\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0433\u0443\u043b\u044b\u0435\u0432\u0438\u0447 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c(\u043c)\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432,\" using various transcriptions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2006/12/56E64767-9340-464A-8C8E-96FC8E277DE1.html |title=Turkmen Assembly Discussing Political Future|publisher=Rferl.org |date=26 December 2006 |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2006/12/26A1157E-4545-4AAE-998F-F15A08AF29AE.html |title=Acting Turkmen President Cleared To Run In February Election |publisher=Rferl.org |date=27 December 2006|accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2006/12/F02EFA71-93BF-478A-9200-D909ECB87380.html |title=Turkmenistan Registers Presidential Candidates |publisher=Rferl.org |date=28 December 2006 |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/country_profiles/1298497.stm |title=Turkmenistan country profile - Overview |publisher=BBC News |date= |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6213875.stm |title=Asia-Pacific &#124; Turkmen 'heir apparent' emerges |publisher=BBC News |date=28 December 2006 |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Than |first=Krisztina |url=http://today.reuters.com/news/articlenews.aspx?type=worldNews&storyID=2006-12-25T142543Z_01_L25241972_RTRUKOC_0_US-TURKMENISTAN.xml&WTmodLoc=IntNewsHome_C2_worldNews-3 |title=Business & Financial News, Breaking US & International News &#124; Reuters.com |publisher=Today.reuters.com |date=9 February 2009 |accessdate=5 September 2015 }}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/27/world/asia/27turkmenistan.html|title=Turkmenistan Limits Election to Soviet-Style Slate|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/30/world/asia/30turkmenistan.html?ref=asia|title=Turkmen Exile Urges Interim President to Step Down|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/world/20061226-1210-turkmenistan-election.html |title=Turkmenistan's interim leader crowned as heir apparent to late dictator |publisher=SignOnSanDiego.com |date=26 December 2006 |accessdate=5 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201034509/http://www.signonsandiego.com/news/world/20061226-1210-turkmenistan-election.html |archivedate=1 February 2009 }}</ref>}}{{efn|The English version of the website of the presidency uses a curious mixture of the Turkmen spelling with a transcribed ending: '''Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov'''<ref>[http://turkmenistan.gov.tm/_en/ Turkmenistan: The Golden Age] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090417014826/http://turkmenistan.gov.tm/_en/ |date=17 April 2009 }}</ref>}} (born 29 June 1957)<ref>{{cite news |title=Turkmenistan: New President Shows Shades Of 'Turkmenbashi' |url=http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2007/07/553cbfb1-46aa-4757-ae2b-2069350baf5f.html |work=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date=3 July 2007 |accessdate=16 July 2007}}</ref> is a [[Turkmenistan|Turkmen]] politician who has been serving as the [[President of Turkmenistan]] since February 2007. Berdimuhamedow, a [[dentistry|dentist]] by profession, served in the government under President [[Saparmurat Niyazov]] as Minister of Health beginning in 1997 and as Vice-President beginning in 2001. He became Acting President following Niyazov's death on 21 December 2006 and subsequently won the [[2007 Turkmen presidential election|February 2007 presidential election]]. He faced no meaningful opposition in the vote and won by an overwhelming margin (89.23%).<ref name=\"sworn\">{{cite news |title=New Turkmen President Sworn In|url=https://www.rferl.org/a/1074693.html |work=Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty |date=14 February 2007 |accessdate=6 March 2007 }}</ref> In the [[2012 Turkmenistani presidential election|February 2012 presidential election]], he was re-elected with 97% of the vote. In the [[2017 Turkmenistani presidential election|February 2017 presidential election]], he was re-elected to a third term with 97.69% of the votes.<ref>[http://www.rferl.org/a/berdymukhammedov-turkmenistan-presidential-election/28304657.html Turkmen President Extends Rule In Tightly Controlled Vote] [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]] (www.rferl.org). 13 February 2017. Retrieved on 24 February 2017.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/world/2012-02/17/c_131416863.htm|title=Turkmen president sworn in for second term|work=xinhuanet.com}}</ref>\n\nAs with his predecessor, a [[Cult of personality|personality cult]] is promoted around Berdimuhamedow. According to [[Human Rights Watch]], Berdimuhamedow, his relatives, and his associates possess unlimited power and exercise [[Totalitarianism|total control over all aspects of public life]].<ref name=\"MyUser_Hrw.org_January_28_2015c\">{{cite web |url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2014/country-chapters/turkmenistan |title=World Report 2014: Turkmenistan |newspaper=Hrw.org |date=  |author= |accessdate= 28 January 2015}}</ref> He uses the honorific title '''Arkadag''', meaning \"protector\" in the [[Turkmen language]].<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://enews.fergananews.com/news.php?id=2003&print=1 |title=Turkmenistan: President Gurbanguly Berdymukhammedov is awarded the status of Arkadag \u2013 protector - Ferghana Information agency, Moscow |publisher=Enews.fergananews.com |date= |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Early years==\nBerdimuhamedow was born on 29 June 1957 in [[Babarap]], in what is now the [[Geok Tepe]] ''etrap'' (\"district\") of [[Ahal Province]], to [[:ru:\u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432, \u041c\u044f\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0433\u0443\u043b\u044b \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0447|M\u00e4likguly Berdimuhamedowi\u00e7 Berdimuhamedow]] and Ogulabat Ata\u00fdewna K\u00fcrr\u00e4\u00fdewa.<ref name=\"arhyw\" /> He is the only son in a family of six children. Berdimuhammedow\u2019s father worked as a senior Interior Ministry officer in a prison guard detachment. He retired as a Colonel of police.<ref name=\"theguardian cables\">[https://amp.theguardian.com/world/us-embassy-cables-documents/240618 US embassy cables: Turkmenistan president 'not a very bright guy'], ''Theguardian.com'', 2 December 2010</ref> Berdimuhammedow graduated from the [[Turkmen State Medical Institute]] in 1979 and entered a career in dentistry.<ref name=\"guardian 2008\">{{cite news|title=And finally... how the march of a lone cockroach put 30 people out of work|publisher = The Guardian |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/feb/22/television| author=Luke Harding|date=22 February 2008|accessdate=22 February 2008}}</ref> He also received a PhD in medical sciences in [[Moscow]].<ref name=\"guardian 2008\"/> By 1992 he had become part of the dentistry faculty at the Medical Institute.\n\nIn 1995, during the rule of [[Saparmurat Niyazov]], Berdimuhamedow became head of the dentistry center of the Ministry of Health and Medical Industry.<ref name=\"bbc profile\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6346185.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Asia-Pacific - Profile: Kurbanguly Berdymukhamedov|work=bbc.co.uk}}</ref> He was appointed to the government as Minister of Health in 1997, and he was additionally appointed as Deputy Chairman of the Cabinet of Ministers (also referred to as [[Deputy Prime Minister]], despite the lack of a Prime Ministerial post in Turkmenistan), a post akin to that of a Vice-President, in 2001.<ref>[http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2006/12/3F7885AA-B6AA-4028-A29C-3CF882FC2FA0.html \"Turkmenistan: Change Of Leadership Presents Many Dangers\"], Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberties, 22 December 2006.</ref><ref>[http://www.press-uz.info/ru/content.scm?topicId=2633&contentId=37772 Press-Uz.info] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930020824/http://www.press-uz.info/ru/content.scm?topicId=2633&contentId=37772 |date=30 September 2007 }}, 22 December 2006 (in [[Russian language|Russian]]).</ref> In April 2004, Niyazov suspended Berdimuhamedow's salary for three months because healthcare workers were not being paid.<ref name=\"bbc profile\"/>\n\n[[File:Vladimir Putin in Turkmenistan 23-24 April 2002-1.jpg|thumb|Berdimuhamedow with Russian President [[Vladimir Putin]] at [[Ashgabat International Airport|Ashgabat Airport]].]]\n\nThe Health Ministry was responsible for carrying out Niyazov's notorious order to close all hospitals outside of the capital city and major regional towns in 2005.<ref>[http://web.amnesty.org/library/Index/ENGEUR610012005?open&of=ENG-348 \"Turkmenistan: President announces large-scale closure of hospitals\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061225003607/http://web.amnesty.org/library/Index/ENGEUR610012005?open&of=ENG-348 |date=25 December 2006 }}, Amnesty International, 24 March 2005.</ref>\n\n==President of Turkmenistan==\n[[File:Dmitry Medvedev in Turkmenistan 13 September 2009-1.jpg|thumb|With [[President of Russia|President]] [[Dmitry Medvedev]] and [[President of Kazakhstan]] [[Nursultan Nazarbayev]]]]\n\nFollowing Niyazov's death in December 2006, the [[State Security Council of Turkmenistan]] appointed Berdimuhamedow as acting president.<ref>[http://www.HVBhlsBDVlchZBDLvbSLvlbl/cis/20061221/57476457.html] {{dead link|date=September 2015}}</ref> The Council stated in its announcement that [[\u00d6wezgeldi Ata\u00fdew]], who, as the Chairman of the [[Assembly of Turkmenistan]] was to become the acting president, was not appointed \"in view of the fact that the prosecutor-general had instituted criminal proceedings against him\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Turkmen Dpty PM Berdymukhammedov appointed acting president|url=http://www.itarass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=11104815|publisher=[[ITAR-TASS]]|date=21 December 2006}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Official welcome ceremony was held for President of Turkmenistan Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow.jpg|thumb|150px|Berdimuhamedow with [[President of Azerbaijan]] [[Ilham Aliyev]].]]\n[[File:Official visit of the President to Turkmenistan 01.jpg|thumb|150px|Berdimuhamedow with [[Petro Poroshenko]].]]\n\nArticle 60 of the Turkmen Constitution stipulated that the acting president \"may not stand for election to the Presidency\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislationline.org/upload/legislations/4f/56/33fa31942510288eb01ea3a1508a.pdf|title=Legislationline.|work=legislationline.org|df=}}{{dead link|date=July 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> which would have barred Berdimuhamedow from running in the 2007 presidential elections. However, on 24 December 2006, the [[People's Council of Turkmenistan|People's Council]] voted to remove this provision, making him eligible for the election as one of the six chosen candidates, all members of the [[Democratic Party of Turkmenistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/6359569.stm |title=Asia-Pacific &#124; New Turkmen leader is inaugurated |publisher=BBC News |date=14 February 2007 |accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref> Berdimuhamedov was supported by the political elite,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.interfax.ru/e/B/politics/28.html?id_issue=11654021|title=Acting leader proposed as candidate for Turkmen president|agency=[[Interfax]]|date=26 December 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930224910/http://www.interfax.ru/e/B/politics/28.html?id_issue=11654021 |archivedate=30 September 2007 }}</ref> and the official results showed him as winning 89% of the vote.<ref name=\"sworn\" /><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20070213014806/http://www.voanews.com/english/2007-02-11-voa13.cfm Turkmenistan Votes for Presidential Successor], ''Voanews.com'', 11 February 2007</ref>\n\nIn his first presidential trip abroad, Berdimuhamedov visited [[Saudi Arabia]] in mid-April 2007. There he performed the [[Umrah]] pilgrimage and met with [[Abdullah of Saudi Arabia|King Abdullah]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cacianalyst.org/newsite/?q=node/4594/print|title=BERDYMUKHAMMEDOV BURNISHES MUSLIM CREDENTIALS ON VISIT TO SAUDI ARABIA|work=cacianalyst.org|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926234552/http://www.cacianalyst.org/newsite/?q=node%2F4594%2Fprint|archivedate=26 September 2007}}</ref> He then visited [[Russia]] and President [[Vladimir Putin]] at the end of the same month.\n\n[[File:Gurbanguly Berdimuhammedov with Obamas.jpg|thumb|Berdimuhamedow with [[President of the United States|US President]] [[Barack Obama]] and [[First Lady of the United States|First Lady]] [[Michelle Obama]]]]\n[[File:Third GECF summit in Tehran 41.jpg|thumb|Berdimuhamedow with Iranian President [[Hassan Rouhani]] during the [[Third GECF summit]]]]\n\nAfter taking office, Berdimuhamedow reversed several of Niyazov's more eccentric policies. Internet caf\u00e9s offering free and uncensored web access opened in [[Ashgabat]],<ref>{{cite news \n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | agency = Associated Press\n  | title = A crack in the isolation of Turkmenistan: Internet cafes\n  | work =\n  | pages =\n  | publisher = USA Today\n  | date = 16 February 2007\n  | url = https://www.usatoday.com/news/world/2007-02-16-turkmenistan_x.htm\n  | accessdate = 26 April 2007 }}\n</ref> compulsory education was extended from nine to ten years and classes in sports and foreign languages were re-introduced into the curriculum, and the government announced plans to open several specialised schools for the arts.<ref>{{cite news \n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = 1 \u0430\u043f\u0440\u0435\u043b\u044f \u0432 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u043e\u044e\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044b \u0438\u0441\u043a\u0443\u0441\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0430\n  | work =\n  | pages =\n  | publisher = G\u00fcndogar\n  | date = 21 February 2007\n  | url = http://www.gundogar.org/?022500000000000000011062007020000#3922\n  | accessdate = 26 April 2007|language=ru}}\n</ref> President Berdimuhamedow has called for reform of education, health care and pension systems, and government officials of non-Turkmen ethnic origin who had been sacked by Niyazov were allowed to return to work.<ref>{{cite news\n |author      = Leila\n |title       = Internet in Turkmenistan: A sign of hope?\n |publisher   = New Eurasia\n |date        = 20 February 2007\n |url         = http://turkmenistan.neweurasia.net/?p=176\n |accessdate  = 26 April 2007\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070516173113/http://turkmenistan.neweurasia.net/?p=176\n |archivedate = 16 May 2007\n}}\n</ref> He also restored the pensions of 100,000 elderly people whose pensions Niyazov had slashed in the face of an unspecified budget crisis.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/03/19/asia/AS-GEN-Turkmenistan-Pensions.php|title=New Turkmen president restores pensions to more than 100,000|periodical=[[International Herald Tribune]]|date=19 March 2007|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081013155211/http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/03/19/asia/AS-GEN-Turkmenistan-Pensions.php |archivedate=13 October 2008 }}</ref> Later on, he reopened the Turkmen Academy of Sciences, which had been closed by Niyazov.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gundogar.org/?024100000000000000011062007060000#4470|title=\u0413\u0443\u043d\u0434\u043e\u0433\u0430\u0440 :: NEWS|work=Gundogar.org|accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, he was reelected to a third term as President of Turkmenistan (seven-year term) with nearly 98% of the votes in his favor and with an eligible voter turnout of 97%.<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2017/02/gurbanguly-berdymukhamedov-wins-poll-98-vote-170213060136393.html Gurbanguly Berdymukhamedov wins poll with 98% of vote], ''Aljazeera.com'', 13 February 2017 \"Turkmenistan's ruling leader Gurbanguly Berdymukhamedov bagged a fresh seven-year term with nearly 98 percent of a weakly contested vote, electoral officials following a preliminary count said. The election commission claimed at a news conference on Monday, in the capital Ashgabat, a turnout of more than 97 percent for the poll,\"</ref><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://learningenglish.voanews.com/a/turkmen-president-elected-98-percent-of-vote/3722818.html|title=Turkmen President Re-elected with 98 Percent of Vote|publisher=[[Voice of America]]|date=13 February 2017|accessdate=8 July 2019|quote=The president of Turkmenistan won re-election with nearly 98 percent of the votes, the country\u2019s election commission reported. President Gurbanguly Berdymukhamedov was elected to a third term which will last for seven years. He was first elected president in 2006. The election results were announced Sunday night by the Central Asian nation\u2019s election commission. The commission said 97 percent of eligible voters turned out to vote.}}</ref> In October 2017, he offered a top Turkmen-bred variety of the Central Asian shepherd dog to [[Vladimir Putin]].<ref>Tim Lister, [https://edition.cnn.com/2017/10/11/world/russia-putin-birthday-puppy-trnd/index.html Pup-lover Putin gifted new dog for birthday], ''CNN'', 12 October 2017</ref>\n\nHe was reelected as president of the [[National Olympic Committee of Turkmenistan]] on 22 April 2018.<ref>{{cite web|date=22 April 2018|url= http://tdh.gov.tm/news/articles.aspx&article12456&cat30|title=President Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov is re-elected the Head of National Olympic Committee |publisher=[[Turkmenistan State News Agency]]|access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Criticism ==\n\n===Accusations of totalitarianism===\n{{see|Human rights in Turkmenistan}}\n[[File:Gurbanguly-Berdimuhamedow-On-Horse.JPG|thumb|Image of Berdimuhamedow, on display outside the national horse-racing ground in Ashgabat, Turkmenistan]]\n{{external media\n| align = right\n| video1  = [https://www.rferl.org/a/our-hero-lavish-praise-for-turkmen-president-s-cutbacks/29521371.html Turkmenistan's president announces end of free gas, electricity, water, and salt]\n| video2  = [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U6I6RtxTpGA Turkmen president visits local village]\n}}\n\nUpon taking office, Berdimuhamedow eased travel restrictions and reopened libraries in rural areas. He also took steps to curb Niyazov's extensive [[Cult of personality|personality cult]]. He called for an end to the elaborate pageants of music and dancing that formerly greeted the president on his arrival anywhere, and said that the Turkmen \"sacred oath\", part of which states that the speaker's tongue should shrivel if he ever speaks ill of Turkmenistan or its president, should not be recited multiple times a day but reserved for \"special occasions.\"<ref>{{cite news \n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = Turkmenistan moves to reduce cult\n  | work =\n  | pages =\n  | publisher = MWC News\n  | date = 10 March 2007\n  | url = http://mwcnews.net/content/view/13117/195/\n  | accessdate = 26 April 2007 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070313203413/http://mwcnews.net/content/view/13117/195/ <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 13 March 2007}}\n</ref> He also gave up his right to rename any landmarks, institutions, or cities,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rferl.org/featuresarticle/2007/03/4649a16c-291d-4855-bc62-4c7018304bff.html|title=Turkmenistan Restricts Presidential Prerogatives|work=RadioFreeEurope/RadioLiberty|accessdate=5 September 2015}}</ref> restored the traditional names of the months of the year and days of the week (Niyazov had renamed them after himself and his mother, among other things),<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7365346.stm | work=BBC News | title=Turkmen go back to old calendar | date=24 April 2008 | accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref> and announced plans to move the infamous [[Neutrality Monument|gold rotating statue]] of Niyazov from Ashgabat's central square.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7382512.stm | work=BBC News | title=Ex-Turkmen leader's statue moved | date=3 May 2008 | accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref> However, he explicitly ruled out any move toward Western-style democracy.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7155476.stm | work=BBC News | title=Fresh optimism in Turkmenistan | date=21 December 2007 | accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, he dismissed [[Akmyrat Rejepow]], the longtime chief of the presidential security detail and one of the main proponents of Niyazov's personality cult.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurasianet.org/departments/insight/articles/pp051607.shtml |title=Turkmenistan: New President Sacks Long-Serving Security Chief |publisher=EurasiaNet.org |date=15 May 2007 |accessdate=5 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924021545/http://www.eurasianet.org/departments/insight/articles/pp051607.shtml |archive-date=24 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> In 2011, he sang a song on a video posted to [[YouTube]].<ref>[https://www.rferl.org/a/chaikhana_talented_mr_berdymukhammedov/24298760.html The Talented Mr. Berdymukhammedov], ''Rferl.org'', 16 August 2011</ref>\n\nIn July 2013, [[Jennifer Lopez]] publicly apologized for singing ''Happy birthday!'' to Berdimuhamedow during a sponsored concert, stating she was not aware of the [[human rights]] issues in Turkmenistan prior to the show.<ref>Jared Anderson, [https://www.cnbc.com/id/100860190 Jennifer Lopez Apologizes for Celebrating Resource-Rich Dictator], ''Cnbc.com'', 2 July 2013</ref> In August 2013, Berdimuhamedow suspended his Democratic Party of Turkmenistan membership for the duration of his presidency, ostensibly to remain \"above partisan politics\" and \"promote a multiparty system.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2013/08/18/world/turkmen-president-quits-top-party/#.Uhc6c5LiH4g|title=Turkmen president quits top party|work=The Japan Times}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2013, he fell off his horse during a race. The fall was censored on TV but leaked online.<ref>[https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/05/01/gurbanguly-berdymukhamedov-turkmenistan-president-falls-off-horse-video_n_3191625.html Gurbanguly Berdymukhamedov, Turkmenistan President, Falls Off Horse During Race (VIDEO)], ''Huffingtonpost.com'', 6 December 2017</ref> On 11 August 2019, an episode of [[HBO]]'s ''[[Last Week Tonight with John Oliver]]'' featured two clips of the incident. This was part of a long piece satirising the dictator, culminating in the unveiling of a 55 sq meter marble cake decorated with a giant image of the president falling off the horse.\n\nIn 2015, a golden statue of Berdimuhamedow riding a horse atop a white-marble cliff was erected in Ashgabat.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/may/25/horse-turkmenistan-president-statute-berdymukhamedov  | work=The Guardian | title=A horse, a horse \u2026 Turkmenistan president honours himself with statue | date=25 May 2015 | accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref><ref>Adam Taylor, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/worldviews/wp/2015/05/25/turkmenistans-leader-infamous-for-falling-off-a-horse-unveils-a-giant-statue-of-himself-riding-a-horse/ Turkmenistan\u2019s leader, infamous for falling off a horse, unveils a giant statue of himself riding a horse], ''Washingtonpost.com'', 25 May 2015</ref>\n\nAccording to international observers, Berdimuhamedow now leads \"one of the most oppressive\" and \"closed\" regimes in the world. [[Freedom House]] has consistently placed Turkmenistan near the bottom of its [[Freedom in the World]] rankings since Berdimuhamedow took office; in 2017, the country was one of 11 with the lowest aggregate scores for political and civil rights.<ref>[https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-world/freedom-world-2017 Freedom in the World 2017]</ref> [[Human Rights Watch]] noted that Berdimuhamedow not only has complete control over public life, but presides over a regime that does not tolerate \"alternative political or religious expression\" and has complete control over the media.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report/2017/country-chapters/turkmenistan |title=World Report 2017: Turkmenistan |publisher=[[Human Rights Watch]] |date=  |author= |accessdate= 30 June 2017}}</ref> [[Reporters Without Borders]] has ranked Turkmenistan near the bottom of its [[Press Freedom Index]] for most of Berdimuhamedow's tenure. In 2017, RWB ranked Turkmenistan 178th out of 180 countries surveyed, ahead of [[Eritrea]] and [[North Korea]]. RSF noted that internet access is heavily censored in Turkmenistan, and that [[satellite dish]]es have been removed by government officials.<ref>[https://rsf.org/en/turkmenistan Turkmenistan] at 2017 [[Press Freedom Index]]</ref>\n\nIn September 2016, the Turkmenistan Parliament abolished term limits for the presidency, which allowed Berdimuhamedow to run for a third term.<ref>Damien Sharkov, [https://www.newsweek.com/turkmenistan-president-gurbanguly-berdimuhamedov-indefinite-rule-498347 Turkmenistan votes to allow president rule indefinitely], ''Newsweek.com'', 14 September 2016</ref>\nIn July 2018, he appeared in a [[rap]] video with his grandson. He had previously lifted weights on camera, and also acted as [[DJ]].<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2018/jul/11/turkmenistans-president-performs-in-rap-video-with-his-grandson-video Turkmenistan's president performs in rap video with his grandson \u2013 video], ''Theguardian.com'', 11 July 2018</ref>\n\nBy decree of Berdymuhamedov in January 2019, the government will gradually end state funding of the [[Academy of Sciences of Turkmenistan]]; it will be phased out in three years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/asia_pacific/turkmenistan-to-cut-state-funding-for-science/2019/01/30/76e9528c-24c5-11e9-b5b4-1d18dfb7b084_story.html?utm_term=.4cc850804028|title=Turkmenistan to cut state funding for science|publisher=The Washington Post|date=2019-01-30|accessdate=2019-08-18}}{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n=== Violation of individual rights ===\nThe ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' magazine named Berdimuhamedow the 5th of the 23 worst dictators in the world. In the Press Freedom Index (Reporters Without Borders), Turkmenistan ranks 176 out of 178.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.obozrevatel.com/news/2010/9/20/391886.htm|title=\u0412 \u0440\u0435\u0439\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0433 \u0445\u0443\u0434\u0448\u0438\u0445 \u0434\u0438\u043a\u0442\u0430\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u043f\u0430\u043b\u043e \u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435 \u0438\u0437 \u0421\u041d\u0413|website=\u041f\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0430|language=ru|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n\nTurkmenistan leads in the number of political prisoners from all countries of the former USSR.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.osce.org/odihr/124153?download=true|title=2014 OSCE Human Dimension Implementation Meeting, Working Session 5, Wednesday 24 September 2014: Rule of Law 2}}</ref>\n\n=== Corruption ===\nThe country's economy is under total state control. Numerous attempts to attract foreign investors into the country often end in lawsuits in international courts. In 2018, the International Center for the Settlement of Investment Disputes (arbitration, part of the World Bank group of organizations) received claims against Turkmenistan from Sece In\u015faat (Turkey) and investment company Unionmatex Industrieanlagen GmbH (Germany).\n\nIn 2019, the Belarusian construction company Belgorkhimprom also filed a similar claim with the court, to which Turkmenistan should pay about $200 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hronikatm.com/2019/02/turkmenhimiya-zadolzhala-belgorhimpromu-bolee-150-mln-za-stroitelstvo-garlykoskogo-gok/|title=\"\u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0445\u0438\u043c\u0438\u044f\" \u0437\u0430\u0434\u043e\u043b\u0436\u0430\u043b\u0430 \"\u0411\u0435\u043b\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0445\u0438\u043c\u043f\u0440\u043e\u043c\u0443\" \u0431\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0435 $150 \u043c\u043b\u043d \u0437\u0430 \u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e \u0413\u0430\u0440\u043b\u044b\u043a\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0413\u041e\u041a\u0425\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430|last=Editor|date=2019-02-01|website=\u0425\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430|language=ru-RU|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://tsn.life/ad-investora-neskolko-realnyx-istorij-lyudej-i-kompanij-reshivshixsya-vlozhit-dengi-v-turkmenistan/|title=\u0410\u0434 \u0438\u043d\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0430. \u041d\u0435\u0441\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u043a\u043e \u0440\u0435\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u043b\u044e\u0434\u0435\u0439 \u0438 \u043a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0439, \u0440\u0435\u0448\u0438\u0432\u0448\u0438\u0445\u0441\u044f \u0432\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0438\u0442\u044c \u0434\u0435\u043d\u044c\u0433\u0438 \u0432 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d}}</ref>\n\nInvestors talk about discrimination against the Turkmen authorities, politicized bureaucracy, and a high level of corruption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://infopressa.com/2019/05/07/kak-tyrkmenistan-kidaia-investorov-podtverjdaet-svoi-podvalnye-indeksy/|title=\u041a\u0430\u043a \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d, \u043a\u0438\u0434\u0430\u044f \u0438\u043d\u0432\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0432, \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0436\u0434\u0430\u0435\u0442 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0432\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0438\u043d\u0434\u0435\u043a\u0441\u044b {{!}} http://infopressa.com|language=ru-RU|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n\nIn the Transparency International Corruption Perception Index, Turkmenistan ranked 161 among 180 countries in 2018. This is the lowest rating among countries in Eastern Europe and Central Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eadaily.com/ru/news/2018/02/22/transparency-international-turkmeniya-lidiruet-v-mirovom-reytinge-korrupcii|title=Transparency International: \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043b\u0438\u0434\u0438\u0440\u0443\u0435\u0442 \u0432 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0435\u0439\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0440\u0443\u043f\u0446\u0438\u0438|website=EADaily|language=ru|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.transparency.org/cpi2018|title=Corruption Perceptions Index 2018|last=e.V|first=Transparency International|website=transparency.org|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Turkmenistan ranked 164th among 180 countries in the ranking of economic freedom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.heritage.org/index/|title=Index of Economic Freedom: Promoting Economic Opportunity and Prosperity by Country|website=heritage.org|language=en|access-date=2019-08-28}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Domestic awards===\n* 1994 \u2013 [[Star of President Order]]\n\n===Foreign awards===\n[[File:The Prime Minister, Shri Narendra Modi presents the President of Turkmenistan, Mr. Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov a specially handcrafted horse saddle, in Ashgabat, Turkmenistan on July 11, 2015.jpg|thumb|A specially handcrafted [[horse saddle]] given to him as a gift from [[Indian Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] in July 2015.]]\n* 2007 \u2013 {{Flag|United Arab Emirates}}: [[Order of Zayed]]{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n* 2007 \u2013 {{Flag|Uzbekistan}}: [[Order of Distinguished Service (Uzbekistan)|Order of Distinguished Service]]{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n* 2008 \u2013 {{Flag|Kazakhstan}}: [[Medal \"10 years of Astana\"]]{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n* 2010 \u2013 {{Flag|Tajikistan}}: [[Order of Ismoili Somoni]]{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n* 2011 \u2013 {{Flag|Bahrain}}: [[Order of Sheikh Isa bin Salman Al Khalifa]]{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n* 2012 \u2013 {{Flag|Turkey}}: First Class of the [[Order of the State of Republic of Turkey]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tccb.gov.tr/konuk-devlet-baskanlari/255/82242/turkmenistan.html|title= Official visit of Turkmenistan|publisher=[[\u00c7ankaya K\u00f6\u015fk\u00fc|Presidency of Republic of Turkey]]|date=29 February 2012|accessdate=25 February 2015}}</ref>\n* 2013 \u2013 {{Flag|Serbia}}: Order of the Republic of Serbia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blic.rs/Vesti/Politika/476971/Nikolic-ordenja-deli-u-tri-smene|title=Blic Online - Nikoli\u0107 ordenja deli u tri smene|work=Blic Online}}</ref>\n* 2016, 2017 \u2013 {{Flag|Moldova}}: [[Order of the Republic (Moldova)]]\n* 2017 \u2013 {{Flag|Russia}}: [[Order of Alexander Nevsky]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://en.kremlin.ru/events/president/transcripts/55753|title=Press statements following Russia-Turkmenistan talks|work=President of Russia|access-date=2 October 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n* 2017 \u2013 {{Flag|Russia}}: [[Order of Dyslyk]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://m.akipress.com/news:608331&#|title=AKIpress News Agency|website=m.akipress.com|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAccording to a [[Diplomatic cable|cable]] from the U.S. embassy in Ashgabat, Berdimuhamedow is married and has three daughters and one son. One of his sons-in-law, Yhlasgeldi Amanov, headed the Turkmen State Agency for Management and Use of Hydrocarbon Resources in London, was later assigned to the Turkmenistan Embassies in Berlin and London, and as of 23 November 2019 was Turkmenistan's consul general in Dubai.<ref name=dubai>{{cite news|url=https://www.hronikatm.com/2019/11/uae-consulate/|title=\u0412 \u0414\u0443\u0431\u0430\u0435 \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u043b\u043e\u0441\u044c \u0442\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u043a\u043e\u043d\u0441\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0441\u0442\u0432\u043e, \u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u0437\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b \u0437\u044f\u0442\u044c \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430|language=Russian|date=24 November 2019|publisher=\u0425\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430}}</ref>  The other son-in-law is also a diplomat, with a prior posting in Paris, but who is currently assigned to Brussels.<ref name=\"theguardian cables\"/>\n\nAccording to the same leaked cables, Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow  has a mistress, Marina, a Russian nurse that he supposedly met earlier in his dentist career. They have a 14-year old daughter together. Berdimuhamedow's wife has been living in London since 2007.<ref name=\"theguardian cables\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://wikileaks.org/cable/2009/12/09ASHGABAT1633.html|title=Cable Viewer|work=wikileaks.org}}</ref>\n\nHis son, [[Serdar Berdimuhamedow]], is a lieutenant colonel in the [[Armed Forces of Turkmenistan|Armed Forces]].<ref>[https://rus.azattyq.org/amp/28823232.html \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043b \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0441\u044b\u043d\u0430 \u043c\u0435\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044c\u044e \u0438\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0435\u0433\u043e \u043e\u0442\u0446\u0430], ''Azattyq.com'', 30 October 2017</ref>  Serdar was appointed governor of Ahal velayat (province) in June 2019.<ref name=ahalhakim>{{cite news|url=https://www.hronikatm.com/2019/06/monarchy/|title=\u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432 \u043d\u0430\u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0438\u043b \u0441\u044b\u043d\u0430 \u0445\u044f\u043a\u0438\u043c\u043e\u043c \u0410\u0445\u0430\u043b\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0432\u0435\u043b\u0430\u044f\u0442\u0430|language=Russian|date=17 June 2019|publisher=\u0425\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430}}</ref>\n\nAt least three of Berdimuhamedow's grandchildren study in Switzerland: Kerimguly, Ogulb\u00e4bek, and A\u00fdg\u00fcl.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://turkmen.news/news/vnuk-berdymuhamedova-obuchaetsya-v-shvejtsarii/|title=\u0412\u043d\u0443\u043a\u0438 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u0443\u0447\u0430\u044e\u0442\u0441\u044f \u0432 \u044d\u043b\u0438\u0442\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0448\u043a\u043e\u043b\u0435 \u0432 \u0428\u0432\u0435\u0439\u0446\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0438 (\u043e\u0431\u043d\u043e\u0432\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043e)|date=30 Jan 2020|publisher=turkmen.news}}</ref>\n\nHis grandfather, Berdimuhamed Annayev, was a veteran of the [[Great Patriotic War]] and since 2018, a posthumous recipient of the Russian [[Order of Honour (Russia)|Order of Honour]].<ref>Sapar Muradov, [http://orient.tm/en/2018/09/27/10427.html Military school named after Berdimuhamed Annayev receives the Medal of Honour, which was awarded to the grandfather of President of Turkmenistan] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180928201030/http://orient.tm/en/2018/09/27/10427.html |date=28 September 2018 }}, ''Orient.tm'', 27 September 2018</ref>  According to a biography of Berdimuhamedow's father published in 2012, Berdimuhamedow has five sisters: Durdynabat (born 1960), Gulnabat (born 1962), M\u00e4hri (born 1964), Guljamal (born 1969), and Oguljamal (born 1974).<ref name=\"arhyw\">{{cite book |title=Watany\u0148 Wepaly Ogly|author=T\u00fcrkmenistany\u0148 Prezidentini\u0148 Arhiw gaznasy|date=2012|publisher=T\u00fcrkmen d\u00f6wlet ne\u015fir\u00fdat gullugy|location=Ashgabat}}</ref>\n\nDuring his spare time from being President, from his dentistry career and from his political career, he writes books that are popular in [[Turkmenistan]] according to Turkmen propaganda.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://austria.tmembassy.gov.tm/en/news/5170|title=BOOKS OF THE PRESIDENT OF TURKMENISTAN - WINNERS OF THE INTERNATIONAL PUBLISHING CONTEST {{!}} VIENNA, REPUBLIC OF AUSTRIA - EMBASSY OF TURKMENISTAN|website=austria.tmembassy.gov.tm|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ahal-teke.org/en/New-Book-vHeavenly-Beautyv-by-President-of-Turkmenistan-Gurbanguly-Berdimuhamedov-p29.html|title=New Book \"Heavenly Beauty\" by President of Turkmenistan Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov {{!}} ahat-teke.org|website=ahal-teke.org|language=en|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://turkmenpetroleum.com/en/2017/07/04/the-book-dedicated-to-the-60th-anniversary-of-president-gurbanguly-berdimuhamedov-was-published/|title=The book dedicated to the 60th anniversary of President Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov was published \u2013 tpetroleum|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref><ref>https://en.hronikatm.com/2016/03/turkmenistan-president-lauds-tea-drinking-in-new-book/</ref> Aside from writing books, he is known for writing songs, DJing and engaging in health activities.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/video/2018/jul/11/turkmenistans-president-performs-in-rap-video-with-his-grandson-video|title=Turkmenistan's president performs in rap video with his grandson \u2013 video|last=Turkmenistan|first=Source: Chronicle of|date=2018-07-11|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-08-23|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Health===\nOn July 20, 2019, the [[YouTube]] channel of a Turkmen opposition media outlet announced that Berdimuhamedow had reportedly died while on holiday at the age of 61. He was said to have been on leave since July 15. These reports were published by multiple Russian media outlets on the next day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://govoritmoskva.ru/news/205038/?print=1|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0441-\u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0430 \u0423\u0437\u0431\u0435\u043a\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u043f\u043e\u0434\u0442\u0432\u0435\u0440\u0434\u0438\u043b\u0430, \u0447\u0442\u043e \u043b\u0438\u0434\u0435\u0440 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u0436\u0438\u0432|website=govoritmoskva.ru|access-date=2019-08-23}}</ref><ref name=\"report\">{{cite web |url=https://gazeta.ru/politics/news/2019/07/21/n_13242091.shtml |title=\u0423\u043c\u0435\u0440 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0437\u0438\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u043a\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0413\u0443\u0440\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0443\u043b\u044b \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0434\u044b\u043c\u0443\u0445\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432, \u0441\u043e\u043e\u0431\u0449\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u0421\u041c\u0418 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190721141702/https://m.gazeta.ru/politics/news/2019/07/21/n_13242091.shtml |archive-date=21 July 2019 |date=21 July 2019 |accessdate=21 July 2019 |work=gazeta.ru |language=ru }}</ref> The Turkmen Ambassador to Kyrgyzstan, Shadurdy Mereov, and the Kyrgyz Ministry of Foreign Affairs denied these claims on 21 July. According to The Chronicle of Turkmenistan, Berdimuhamedow went to [[Germany]] because his mother was receiving medical treatment there, and her condition was critical.<ref name=\"mereov\">{{cite web |url=https://m.akipress.com/news:622368/ |title=Embassy of Turkmenistan refutes media reports about death of Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedov |date=21 July 2019 |accessdate=21 July 2019 |work=Akipress.com }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Politics of Turkmenistan]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Gurbanguly Berdimuhamedow}}\n{{Wikiquote|Gurbanguly Berdimuhammedov}}\n* [http://turkmenistan.gov.tm/_eng/ Presidency's official website]\n* [https://www.instagram.com/gmberdimuhamedow/ Berdimuhamedow's Instagram Page]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Orazgeldi A\u00fddogdyew]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Vice-President of Turkmenistan|years=2001\u20132007}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ra\u015fit Meredow]]}}\n{{s-break}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Saparmurat Niyazov]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[President of Turkmenistan]]|years=2007\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Heads of government of Turkmenistan}}\n{{Prime Ministers of Turkmenistan}}\n{{Current ECO Leaders}}\n{{Current CIS Leaders}}\